<HEAD>Government Frees 29 Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANTASMA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Sandinista government on Tuesday freed 29 peasants accused of collaborating with U.S.-backed rebels _ the first of about 1,200 prisoners <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has promised to release. The 29 were freed from a city jail in this northern town. `` This should coincide with the beginning of the demobilization of the Contras -LRB- rebels -RRB- from <LOCATION> Honduran </LOCATION> territory and the withdrawal of those who operate in Nicaraguan territory,'' President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. He said there will be no mercy for rebel groups who do not disband in compliance with the peace agreement signed last week in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and four other Central American presidents. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> spoke at a cermony during the release of the 29 in <LOCATION> Pantasma </LOCATION>, 140 miles north of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. `` He who does not accept the hand we are extending should be prepared,'' he said. Under the agreement signed at the summit conference in <LOCATION> Tela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, the rebels are to disband by early December. An estimated 11,000 Contras and 12,000 dependents will be moved from camps along the Honduran border and resettled in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, under the accords. The government said recently there are about 2,500 Contras operating in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. In return for the disbanding of the rebels the government has pledged to hold free and fair elections in February. It would be the first free vote since the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> defeated the conservative government of President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> and gained power in July 1979. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said the rebels `` have the opportunity to contribute to peace in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'' and `` avoid more suffering for their families.'' On Sunday, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> agreed to a request from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> and Cattlemen to release about 1,200 peasants accused of aiding the rebels. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said Tuesday that 1,515 rebels and 39 former national guardsmen in the Somoza regime are in Nicaraguan prisons. The government freed 1,897 former guardsmen on March 17. The leftis government has announced monthly cease-fires in its war against the rebels since June 1988, when a temporary truce between the two sides expired. Pantasma is located in a northern valley the rebels tried to take numerous times but failed. In October 1983, 48 peasants died in the fighting.
