<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Jeeps     08-15 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Jeeps,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>The American Jeep Is Mark of Prestige to Japanese 4WD Enthusiasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOTOSU, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Japanese have gone wild over four-wheel drive vehicles and on that score they have shed their prejudices against American automobiles. The American-made Jeep is the mark of prestige. Churning up mud, bouncing over dirt moguls, mucking through boggy sinkholes, enthusiasts careen around a 5.5-acre four-wheel-drive playground in the shadow of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fuji </LOCATION>. The equivalent of a ski resort for dirt vehicles, the pay-by-the-day <LOCATION> Motosu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highlands </LOCATION> course is flourishing because herds of four-wheel-drive vehicles were banned from tearing up <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fuji </LOCATION> itself. But the four-wheel-drive vehicle also has become a status symbol in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s high-fashion <LOCATION> Harajuku </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, where urban dandies cruise around in chrome-trimmed, jacked-up, jeep-type vehicles with the tops down, festooned with macho but unused heavy-duty winches and fog lights. And in affluent residential neighborhoods, housewives load groceries into Jeep Cherokees parked next to Mercedes Benzes and Saabs. In a country eager for ever-more-stylish ways to spend new-found cash, four-wheel-drive recreational vehicles have become the ultimate Japanese yuppie vehicle _ and the American Jeep is the one to own. While other American cars are deemed mediocre by the Japanese, Jeeps evoke an image of American wide-open spaces and outdoor life that many Japanese long for, says <PERSON> Nobuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Fukushima </PERSON>, editor of 4X4 Magazine. Chrysler Jeep sales have doubled in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for three years in a row, but they still totaled only 500 in 1988. The vast majority of four-wheel-drive cars on Japanese roads are still domestic models, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> Pajero or Isuzu Big Horn. And many vehicles with the genuine Jeep insignia were built by <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION>, which bought the technology from the <ORGANIZATION> Willis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Overland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> more than 20 years ago, before Jeep manufacturing was taken over in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and then <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>. Four-wheel-drive vehicles are the fastest-growing segment of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s auto market. For the past few years jeep-type sales have grown 20 to 30 percent annually, or three times as fast as the entire car market, estimates <PERSON> Fukushima </PERSON>. One in 11 of the 6.7 million cars produced in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> last year had four-wheel drive. Recreation vehicles are part of a growing leisure industry fueled by rising incomes and longer vacations. Skiers, surfers, and scuba divers also are avid drivers of jeep-style vehicles. But 75 percent of four-wheel-drives in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> never leave city streets: their appeal is atmospheric rather than functional. Jeep-style vehicles with power steering, leather seats, stereos, adjustable suspensions and automatic transmissions sell fast, and dealers say they're getting BMW trade-ins from buyers. The top-of-the-line <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jeep Cherokee costs about $ 35,000 in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, more than double the price of many smaller Japanese jeep-style cars. `` This is really a luxury car, for well-to-do buyers, mostly professionals in their late 30s or 40s,'' says <PERSON> Masayuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakamoto </PERSON>, director of marketing for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Masaaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuroiwa </PERSON>, who has been selling Jeeps and Jeep parts for more than 20 years from a cluttered suburban garage, finds the fad a little ironic `` There's no need for these cars in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> nowadays,'' he said. `` There's hardly any place to really drive them. It's just a fashion, people like them with all kinds of shiny accessories stuck on. It's a way to spend money.'' <PERSON> Kuroiwa </PERSON> fell in love with Jeeps when they were the only vehicles that could get around in a devastated <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> just after World War II. As a child he admired the powerful olive-green vehicles driven by American occupation troops. After the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> occupation forces left <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, their Jeeps continued to serve as all-round vehicles, especially on rough country roads, but they nearly disappeared in the 1960s, when many were shipped to poorer countries for another lifetime of service. Now <PERSON> Kuroiwa </PERSON> and others are buying vintage <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jeeps </ORGANIZATION> as collectors items from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, where they are still widely in use. In <PERSON> Kuroiwa </PERSON>'s lot, <PERSON> Yuichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Tanaka </PERSON>, 45, proudly pats the hood of his well-preserved Jeep, which is exactly as old as he is. `` It's won a lot of Jeep beauty contests,'' he said.
</TEXT>
