<FIRST>r a PM-FarmHotLine     08-15 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Hot Line,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Ends Farm Hot Line; Farmers And Advisers Wiser</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, ILL. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The farm crisis hot line is disconnected, but officials say farmers and <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> advisers who help them are wiser because of Rural Route. The unique program ended this summer after 3,500 farmers called its toll-free number seeking confidential advice about their financial problems. Rural Route, which received $ 2.2 million in state and federal funds over four years, has left both farmers and advisers better prepared for the future, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloome </PERSON>, assistant director of the university <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` They have a vivid memory of a recent event that will make them more cautious,'' he said. Farmers also have learned that farming is a business and that they `` have a value and worth that has nothing to do with that occupation.'' Rural Route also taught university advisers to be aggressive in looking for solutions to farmers' economic problems, and preparing farmers for their future in agriculture or in some other occupation if necessary, said <PERSON> Bloome </PERSON>. `` Some wanted to pretend the men in trouble were older, poorly educated smaller farmers who were laggards at accepting technology,'' he said. `` The opposite was true. They were young, well-educated and progressive.'' The hot line was unplugged July 1, although the services remain available. `` Calls had dropped to one a day or less,'' said <PERSON> Bloome </PERSON>. `` The overall financial picture for farmers was much improved, and farmers' need for anonymity seemed to be less.'' When the first call came into Rural Route, on March 18, 1985, farm income was down, debt and operating costs were up, and many farmers felt a serious economic pinch. Bills _ and stress _ mounted. Foreclosure loomed for some. There was an increase in alcohol abuse, family discord, divorce and suicide. But many troubled farmers refused to seek help because of pride and fear of ridicule in their communities. Farmers were referred to counseling centers around the state, or advisers _ always from <LOCATION> another </LOCATION> <LOCATION> county </LOCATION> _ were dispatched to their farms.
</TEXT>
