<SECOND>AM-Japan-Child Murder,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Confesses to Murdering Three Girls in Series of Abduction Cases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man arrested for kidnapping and killing a five-year-old girl confessed he killed two other girls in a series of brutal murders that have shocked <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, police said Tuesday. <PERSON> Tsutomu </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>, who was arrested Friday for kidnapping and killing <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> <PERSON> Nomoto </PERSON> two months ago, confessed to police that he also killed two 4-year-old girls, <PERSON> Mari </PERSON> <PERSON> Konno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Erika </PERSON> <PERSON> Namba </PERSON>. Police were also grilling the 26-year-old <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> print shop worker regarding his possible involvement in the disappearance of a fourth girl, 7-year-old <PERSON> Masami </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshizawa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Saitama </LOCATION> state, who vanished last October. <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> was in custody after being arrested July 23 for allegedly taking nude photographs of a 6-year-old girl. He was charged with indecent assault in the case. <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> was re-arrested Friday on charges of kidnapping and killing <PERSON> Nomoto </PERSON>, who he told police `` made fun of a deformity'' in his hands. Her torso was found near a public restroom in a cemetery northwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on June 11. Police discovered the girl's skull Thursday at a location <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> led them to. Under Japanese law, prosecutors have a maximum of 20 days to collect evidence against him before releasing him or bringing charges. `` In the most brutal murder case in postwar crime history, <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> finally confessed he killed the other two,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported. The new development appeared on the front pages of all the major Japanese papers. Reporters have been camping out in front of <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>'s house, as well as the victims' homes. In his confession statement, <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> said, `` On Aug. 22, I picked up <PERSON> Mari </PERSON>, drove her to a mountain, where I strangled her to death. I took two pictures of her in the car. I burned her with other things in the front yard at my house. I put her bones and ashes in a box and put it at the front door of <PERSON> Mari </PERSON>'s home,'' the police reported the letter said. In February, after the box was found, letters were sent to <PERSON> Konno </PERSON>'s home and the national newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> by a writer named `` <PERSON> Yuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Imada </PERSON>,'' claiming responsibility for her abduction and murder. Investigators later found that `` <PERSON> Yuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Imada </PERSON>'' was a name of a female detective in a comic book. <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> told police he also kidnapped <PERSON> Namba </PERSON>, strangling her in his car, stripping her clothes off and throwing her in the woods, police said. <PERSON> Mitsuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Maniwa </PERSON>, a psychology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Shizuoka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> could not distinguish between reality and the fictional world largely due to his fascination with horror and animation videos. <PERSON> Susumu </PERSON> <PERSON> Oda </PERSON>, a mental health expert at <ORGANIZATION> Tsukuba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> described the series of abductions as `` murder for pleasure.'' `` This case involved abnormal sexual desires, especially toward little girls, sadism, obsession for dead bodies and objects,'' <PERSON> Oda </PERSON> said.
