<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Haven     08-15 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Haven,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary a Haven for East Europeans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This communist land of comparative plenty, long a magnet for Soviet bloc citizens seeking consumer goods and comfortable vacations, also is becoming an escape route to the West. On Sunday night, a dozen young East Germans who spent the weekend outside the West German consulate in hopes of reaching the West crawled into their sleeping bags for another night on the sidewalk. Police drove by now and then, but did not disturb them. Across the <LOCATION> Danube </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, a new <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> committee was examining requests for refugee status from 10 applicants: a Soviet citizen, a Czechoslovak and eight stranded Somalis. Three refugee camps for 1,400 people are being built outside <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. They are primarily intended for ethnic Hungarians from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, but officials say the camps will be open to all Europeans who can prove they face persecution at home. One of the young East Germans said: `` We still do n't know whether we'll make it, but the way West is a lot easier from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> than from <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> began welcoming Romanian refugees in January 1988, breaking an agreement with the communist ally to return its citizens who sought asylum. About 17,000 Romanians, most of them ethnic Hungarians, have fled to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in the first instance of one <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact country giving sanctuary to citizens of another on grounds of persecution. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s decision to take in refugees from <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> put a further burden on the already strained relations between the two allies. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has long maintained the estimated 1.7 million-member ethnic Hungarian minority in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> is subject to discriminatory policies. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> also has expressed concern over a Romanian plan to demolish villages and resettle the population. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> fears that this could destroy ethnic culture and traditions. <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> rejects the charges as interference in its internal affairs. Hungarian officials said in recent interviews the country will not change its new border and refugee policies just to avoid tensions with allies. In May, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> began dismantling barbed wire and other barriers on its border with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Since then, at least 1,500 East Germans with few chances of travel to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> have tried to cross into <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> illegally through <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Hundreds succeeded and have gone on to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Other hundreds who failed have gone underground in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> or sought asylum on West German diplomatic property. Police Col. <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> urged all people who are in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> illegally to leave, but also told reporters none would be `` forcibly deported.'' A government official said privately: `` Because this decision expands the possibility for the East Germans to go to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> illegally, it's clear that this decision is not among those that the East Germans are happy about.'' The new refugee policy, which could provide asylum to any East European who proved persecution, is likely to disturb <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s East European allies even more. On March 14, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> became the first Soviet bloc country to join the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> on the Rights of Refugees, which took effect June 12. It commits authorities not to return anyone to a country where his `` life or freedom would be threatened on account of his race, religion, nationality ... or political opinion.'' Some Western countries have applied the convention broadly, giving asylum to most citizens of Soviet bloc countries. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> insists <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> does not want to become a conduit to the West, but officials formulating new laws to conform with the convention say all cases will be heard. `` If an individual meets the criteria of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> convention, then we will definitely grant him refugee status, because if we decided to accept something we have to carry it through,'' said <PERSON> Laszlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Albrecht </PERSON>, deputy head of the ministry's refugee section. `` I can not speak for the Czechoslovak or East German governments, but in case they disapprove, what can we do?'' Under new laws taking effect in October, each applicant will be heard by a refugee camp panel, <PERSON> Albrecht </PERSON> said. A refugee who is rejected may appeal to an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> committee, then demand a court hearing. <PERSON> Albrecht </PERSON> said other countries of permanent residence would be sought for most refugees other than ethnic Hungarians, indicating most would come from the East and go West. `` It's clear that not too many Swiss citizens are going to ask for refugee status from us,'' he said, and smiled.
