<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> officials say they are changing some of their business procedures after agreeing to pay a $ 75,000 fine for alleged federal consumer violations. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the financially hobbled carrier agreed to pay the civil penalty `` to avoid costly litigation,'' but was not conceding guilt. The alleged violations occurred in 1986 and 1987. It could take the government years to pocket the funds, however, because <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has been under the protection of federal bankruptcy laws since March 9, five days after the strike against the carrier began. When a bankruptcy judge approves a schedule for repaying creditors, the payments might take years. The DOT charged the airline with taking more than the required seven days to issue credit-card refunds to customers. It also accused Eastern of not informing some consumers that flights listed by the carrier were operated by independent commuter airlines with agreements with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>. Eastern officials said little about the settlement. But spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON> said the company had `` changed our procedures to better comply with DOT regulations.'' DOT officials said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> uses an express delivery service to speed the shipment of refund claims to its <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> headquarters. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay a $ 325,000 fine in November 1987, the largest ever. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> _ like <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ agreed to pay a $ 250,000 penalty for similar charges in June 1987. Eastern filed a reorganization plan with the federal bankruptcy court July 21. Its goal is to emerge from reorganization by the end of this year. Under the agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION>, the government would receive its payment after all creditors have been repaid but before <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s debts to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> are repaid. If the agreement is n't approved by the court by Nov. 30, it would be voided and the government would have to renew its efforts to press its case against <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Podberesky </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> assistant general counsel, said the fine could be repaid in the next few months or could be delayed until sometime in the 1990s. Typically, he said, fines levied against financially healthy airlines are paid within anywhere from 15 days to two years. Claims against carriers in bankruptcy can take years, he said. Eastern, which operated 1,100 flights daily before the strike, operated 350 flights Monday and planned to increase that to 390 Tuesday, <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON> said.
