<HEAD>Congressmen Seek to Curb Pentagon in Rulings on Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are making a new bid to curb the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s power to stop exports of high-technology goods, but defense officials say the limits are needed to keep equipment out of communist hands. Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON>, D-Ore., and others say the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> should oversee shipments of goods with both military and civilian uses, as long as the goods are not being sold to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> or other Communist-ruled countries `` I think it makes sense,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., who heads the subcommittee on international trade in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` I ca n't commit myself now, but I ` ll be glad to look at a proposal.'' Supporters of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on the issue include Sens. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Ill., and Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Bereuter </PERSON>, Members interested in changing the trade rules worry that the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is overzealous in blocking exports. They see <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business losing sales to foreign competitors when more sales are needed to reduce the trade deficit. At the current rate, the trade deficit will be $ 111 billion this year. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, however, has told the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> its work on export licenses has `` resulted in denial of license application to known diverters in <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> countries, at an estimated value of approximately $ 200 million.'' Sensitive goods shipped to allies have sometimes reached Soviet hands. The Japanese government found that <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had sold the Soviets sophisticated machinery capable of silencing submarine propellers. At one point, some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> showed their anger by destroying a <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> radio with hammers on the Capitol lawn. When <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> returns from vacation next month, <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON> and other advocates of the change will sound out opinion in both Houses. <PERSON> AuCoin </PERSON> represents a district where there are many high-technology companies. The new effort in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would not keep the Pentagon out of decisions on exports that go directly to communist-ruled countries, or on exports of purely military goods. The countries on which the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> would continue to have its say include <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted last year to let the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> oversee exports to non-communist countries of technology with non-military uses, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would not go along. Commerce Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosbacher </PERSON> won a decision from President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> against the Pentagon last month on a similar issue, enabling American manufacturers to ship higher-powered computers to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as well as to other countries _ despite public opposition from <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>. `` We did have a difference inside the administration on this question,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told reporters at the time. `` This will not endanger the legitimate national security needs of this country.''
