<HEAD>US Distressed Soviets Didn't Heed Appeals on Missile Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is upset that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> ignored two high-level <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appeals to change its plans to test a long-range missile that passed near the Hawaiian islands. `` There was no danger, but there is always a risk, however slight,'' a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Monday after Friday's 8,000-mile flight of an unarmed intercontinental ballistic missile was disclosed. The missile did n't pass over land while flying over the island chain, but a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said the point of the complaint was that `` it was too close for comfort.'' The missile was launched from the Tyuratam installation deep in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and splashed down some 1,250 miles south of <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>, officials said. Two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the missile had passed over waters between two tiny Hawaiian islands, <PERSON> Neckar </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Nihoa </LOCATION>. A third official confirmed that the Soviets conducted the test Friday despite <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appeals that it posed potential political and safety problems. The Soviets announced Aug. 7 that they intended to conduct a test between Aug. 11 and Aug. 21, but neither of the two private <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appeals to Deputy Ambassador <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> Chetverikov </PERSON> nor the test itself were made public. `` It's somewhat disturbing the Soviets did n't take our concerns into account,'' a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Monday. `` There was no danger, but there is always a risk, however slight, it might be that something would go awry. That is why we felt it was inappropriate.'' Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON> and his dep