<HEAD>Judicial College Teaches Judges How to Better Fight War on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Outrage over drug-related crime has spawned calls for more police and prisons, but a school for judges hopes to teach jurists to wage war on drugs with treatment rather than tough jail terms. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> is launching an instructional program to show judges how to handle criminals who have drug problems. `` There's an onslaught of drug-related cases coming into the courts right now across the country,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, assistant dean of the Reno-based institution. `` What we're trying to do is teach judges patterns of drug use and about evaluation and treatment programs so they do n't just order criminals to be locked up every time.'' One judge in each state has been invited to enroll in the inaugural one-week program, which begins Sunday, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said. At least 44 judges selected by each state's chief judge plan to attend. The course will become a regular offering next March at the judicial college, whose alumni range from local judges to <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. The school offers short courses, mostly lasting one to four weeks. They range from basic instruction for new appointees to the bench, to retraining for experienced jurists. The private school, located on the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> campus, is funded by state and federal grants, as well as tuition. <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Getty </PERSON>, one of the main instructors for next week's course, said he aims to teach jurists to recognize when it would be better to sentence a criminal to treatment instead of prison time. `` Neither the penitentiary nor probation by themselves are an adequate response to this country's drug crimes problems,'' <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, for example, <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> said judges sometimes sentence non-violent criminals who have drug problems to residential or non-residential treatment programs along with community service. `` The recidivism rate for treatment programs is not as high as if you send them to prison,'' he said. `` From that point of view, these types of programs are a tremendous success.'' That message appears to stand in contrast to increasingly strident calls for tougher law enforcement. Last week, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> outlined the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's $ 1 billion crime-fighting package, including harsher penalties for the criminal use of guns, ending plea bargaining in such cases, hiring more investigators and prosecutors and doubling space in federal prisons. <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> said drug-using criminals who commit violent crimes must pay through incarceration. `` I'm not advocating that all drug offenders not go to prison,'' he said. `` But there are a significant number who ought to be placed in treatment programs rather than prisons.'' According to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislatures </ORGANIZATION>, 62 percent of the 605,000 people in state and federal prisons in 1988 used drugs regularly before they were incarcerated. Of those, 27 percent used drugs daily, according to <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunzeker </PERSON>, criminal justice program manager for the national lawmakers group. Twenty-two percent were under the influence of drugs while committing the crime for which they were sentenced to prison, she added. `` The studies show that drug use accelerates criminal behavior,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hunzeker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, the assistant dean, said he hopes that by treating people for drug problems, crime can be reduced. `` Part of the solution to reducing the high crime rate is to find the problems and deal directly with them,'' <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said. `` The role of the judge will be to recognize when the problem is drugs.''
