<HEAD>Key Dates in Botha's Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Key dates in the life of P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. Jan. 12, 1916 _ Born on farm in the Orange Free State. May 1, 1936 _ Quits university to take job as an organizer for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> province. 1939-1940 _ Helps form <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> province </LOCATION> branch of the Ossewabrandwag -LRB- Ox-Wagon Fire Guard -RRB-, a group sympathetic to the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> and opposed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> joining the Allied side in World War II. Threatened with internment but turns against the Ossewabrandwag when it split with <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders. March 13, 1943 _ Marries <PERSON> Elize </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossouw </PERSON>. May 26, 1948 _ Becomes a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from <PERSON> George </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> province </LOCATION> as his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> comes to power. October, 1958 _ Is appointed deputy minister of the interior. Duties include close involvement with administering the Group Areas Act, which segregates residential and business areas by race. Aug. 2, 1961 _ Becomes a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister in charge of community development and colored -LRB- mixed-race -RRB- affairs. April 5, 1966 _ Becomes minister of defense, and is instrumental in making <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> nearly self-sufficient in arms despite a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> arms embargo. 1966 _ Is elected leader of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> province </LOCATION>, one of four powerful provincial leadership posts from which party leaders are chosen. Sept. 28, 1978 _ <ORGANIZATION> Becomes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader and prime minister, following resignation of <PERSON> B.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Vorster </PERSON>. 1979 _ Becomes first national leader to visit a black township, <LOCATION> Soweto </LOCATION>. 1982 _ <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> right-wing breaks away, forming <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, in response to <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s plans to include Indians and people of mixed-race in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, in separate chambers. Meets with Zambian President <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaunda </PERSON>. 1984 _ New constitution is adopted, creating the three-chambered <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that excludes the black majority, and changes <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s title from prime minister to president, with wide-ranging powers Tours <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and declares, `` Apartheid is dead.'' June 12, 1986 _ Declares national emergency to subdue unrest and nationwide violence that erupted in black communities in response to the new constitution. Jan. 18, 1989 _ Suffers a stroke and subsequently gives up leadership of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. March, 1989 _ Under pressure from party leaders, agrees to resign from presidency following Sept. 6 parliamentary elections. July 5, 1989 _ Invites imprisoned <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> to his official <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> residence for conversation. Aug. 14, 1989 _ Announces his resignation.
