<HEAD>Pravda Blasts Baltics for `Nationalist Hysteria'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda today blasted extremists and growing `` nationalist hysteria'' in the Baltic region for labor unrest that is now its seventh day in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. `` Openly anti-Soviet groups have become activized'' in the three Baltic republics and `` a situation is building up of nationalist hysteria,'' the newspaper said in an unsigned commentary. In two other Soviet areas threatened by labor unrest, the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> republics of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, officials said today that all was quiet. <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief called Monday for <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> workers in his tiny republic to end the strike and negotiate differences. But in the Estonian capital of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>, strike committee member <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Lysenko </PERSON> said today that thousands of <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> workers at about 50 factories stayed off the job to protest a new law that tightens residency requirements for voters and candidates. Pravda aimed its criticism at the law rather than the strikers, saying `` the passage of discriminatory acts has an extremely destabilizing influence on the political situation.'' Pravda's comments reflected <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s unease with the grassroots nationalist movements that have swept the Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. The movements, known as People's Fronts, have moved from focusing on support for President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms to `` narrow nationalist positions,'' Pravda said. It complained that the fronts had taken to attacking the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for neglecting the interests of non-Russian populations, and that `` certain forces'' were pushing for complete secession from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Pravda also criticized the Baltic movements for sending emissaries around the country to spread their ideas, and `` using foreign ties more and more often for the same destructive goals.'' It proposed political dialogue as the only means of defusing the situation. Estonian party chief <PERSON> Vaino </PERSON> <PERSON> Vyalyas </PERSON> said Monday that dialogue had not succeeded in resolving the strike, but that he was not ready to give up. `` We met with strike committee representatives and they later said they were not satisfied with the results. If so, let's continue the talks,'' <PERSON> Vyalyas </PERSON> said in an Estonian television interview. State-run <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said the Estonian law will take the right to vote away from more than 100,000 non-Estonians in the republic of 1.6 million people. The new law limits voting to residents who have lived in the same district for two years, or anywhere in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for five years. Candidates must live in the same place for five years, or in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for 10 years. <PERSON> Vyalyas </PERSON> admitted the rights of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s minorities _ whom he did not identify but presumably including Russians _ had not been taken into account. `` This is our mistake and it must be corrected,'' he said. Estonians say residence requirements for voters and candidates are legitimate measures used around the world. But one strike leader said if Americans had a similar law, they would have to wait five years to be able to vote after moving from one state to another. The strike has already cost millions of dollars, <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said. The striking Russians, most of whom work in heavy industrial plants, also object to a new national decision to give <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> free rein over its economy. The workers are demanding that factories with a predominantly Russian-speaking labor force remain the property of the national government rather than be handed over to <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>.
