<HEAD>Plane Lands Safely After Mobile Phone Sets Off Smoke Detector</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An incoming call to a mobile phone in luggage aboard a commuter plane apparently triggered a smoke alarm, forcing the pilot to make an emergency landing, a federal official said. The <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> I plane carrying seven passengers and two crew members landed without incident Monday and no one was injured, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> supervisor at <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Columbus-to-Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> flight was about three miles outside <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> when a detector light was activated, indicating smoke in the baggage area, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. The pilot of the twin-engine, turbo-prop plane radioed the airport about 5:30 p.m. and emergency vehicles were called out to the runway, he said. After the plane landed, the crew discovered a cellular telephone in a passenger's suitcase, and determined a call had caused the problem, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. The flight continued to <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> after the telephone was shut off, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. Express Airlines I, based in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, operates the plane under a marketing agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>.
