<HEAD>Marine With AIDS Suing Navy for Medical Malpractice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Marine has filed a $ 55 million suit against the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> charging that malpractice forced his wife to have a blood transfusion that left her infected with AIDS, which she passed on to him and their son. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON>, 40, a chief warrant officer at the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, contends that <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> doctors mishandled his wife's pregnancy in 1981, resulting in a stillbirth and the need for a transfusion At the time, little was known about AIDS, and donated blood was not routinely screened for the virus. But <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON>'s suit, which is scheduled to go to trial Aug. 21 in federal court, says the transfusion would not have been needed had doctors properly treated his wife, <PERSON> Mutsuko </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON> died of AIDS in 1987, shortly after the lawsuit was filed. The Gaffneys' son, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON>, was born with AIDS and died in 1986 at the age of 13 months. The only member of the family to be spared infection was their 6-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Maureene </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON> himself has tested positive for the virus, although he has not yet shown any symptoms. <PERSON> Marianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowler </PERSON>, an assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney who is representing the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, declined to comment on the case. <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Jaclyn </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenney </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> investigators traced one of the units of blood that <PERSON> Mutsuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON> received to a discharged Marine. A deposition from the blood donor, identified as `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON>'' in court records, shows he has refused to be tested for AIDS because he fears the result might prevent him from getting jobs and health insurance. Mrs. <PERSON> Gaffney </PERSON> was under the care of doctors at <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> when she delivered the stillborn baby four weeks overdue. The doctors had declined to induce labor earlier or to perform a caesarian section to deliver the baby, the lawsuit says.
