<HEAD>Demonstrators Climb Trees Across Nation to Protest Forest Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Environmental activists from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> took to the treetops to voice their opposition to logging in the country's remaining virgin timberlands. Protesters set up camps in trees to coincide with the first of four hearings by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> on its proposal to list the northern spotted owl as a threatened species. Environmentalists say the owl requires old-growth forests for its habitat; the forest-products industry says many logging and mill jobs would be lost if the owl is protected by setting aside forest in protected zones. `` This is obviously spotted owl week throughout the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Darryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Cherney </PERSON>, an Earth First! spokesman involved in the protests near <LOCATION> Ukiah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` The timber crisis is culminating to such an extent right now, that now's the time'' for action. Earth First!, known for putting spikes in trees to discourage logging, said its `` aerial occupations'' had protesters sitting on 3-by-6-foot platforms suspended in trees. They were equipped with food, water and other gear, and supported by ground crews, <PERSON> Cherney </PERSON> said. The protests began Sunday or Monday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cherney </PERSON> said. Others were planned in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Some protesters said they were prepared to stay in the trees for weeks. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, 31, lodged himself 50 feet high in an evergreen outside <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>'s office in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, Ore. He said he had enough food and water to last at least four days. <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> was the site Monday of the first hearing, at which a top official in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said the spotted owl can survive without being listed as a threatened species under federal wildlife protection law. <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Salwasser </PERSON>, deputy director for wildlife and fisheries, said his agency is managing timberlands with the aim of ensuring the owl's long-term survival. Although the hearings were supposed to center on the biological concerns of the owl, many loggers testified about the economic consequences they feared if logging is restricted. Federal judges already have halted timber sales in the region because of lawsuits filed by environmentalists. `` To tell you the truth, I'm scared to death,'' said <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> as he held his 3-year-old son, <PERSON> Adam </PERSON>, in his arms. Hall, a superintendent for High Cascade Lumber in <LOCATION> Skamania </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, said his mill is expected to run out of logs _ and jobs _ in November. <PERSON> Cherney </PERSON> said the demonstrations were not just about the spotted owl, but included concerns over forest resources in general. `` If someone's sitting in a second-growth tree our message is: Let some of these second-growth forests become old-growth forests,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baker-Snoqualmie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, three demonstrators climbed trees in the Goodman Ridge timber sale in an attempt to stop logging, said <PERSON> Janine </PERSON> <PERSON> Blaeloch </PERSON>, an Earth First! spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordova </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, said he knew of no agency policy for dealing with such protests and that decisions were made at the scene. `` We do n't want to violate anyone's constitutional rights to free expression, but we also want to guarantee ... that logging operations are able to continue,'' he said.
