<HEAD>Murders of Young Girls Terrify Tokyo Suburbs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man arrested in connection with the kidnapping and slaying of a 5-year-old girl has confessed to killing two other girls in a series of cases that have brought fear to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> suburbs, police said today. In a society remarkably free of crime, the brutality of the murders in an area northwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> has shocked many Japanese and dominated news and television reports. The cases, however, also have drawn attention to the many animated films available in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> that show violence and scenes of undressed girls and comic books involving crime. The suspect, <PERSON> Tsutomu </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>, said he collected them. <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>, the 26-year-old son of a printing shop owner, was arrested Friday in the kidnapping and killing of 5-year-old <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> <PERSON> Nomoto </PERSON> two months ago. On Sunday, police said he confessed to killing two 4-year-old girls, <PERSON> Mari </PERSON> <PERSON> Konno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Erika </PERSON> <PERSON> Namba </PERSON>. Police said they also were questioning <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> about whether he was involved in the disappearance of a fourth girl, 7-year-old <PERSON> Masami </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshizawa </PERSON>, missing since October. <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> was first arrested July 23 for allegedly forcing a 6-year-old girl to let him take nude pictures of her. During questioning, he admitted to having killed <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> and directed police to a wooded area where her skull was found, police said. Police said <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> told them he had picked up <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> in his car but became angry when she `` made fun of a deformity'' in his hands and strangled her. He then took her body to his room, where he chopped off her head, hands and feet, they said. Her torso was found northwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on June 11. `` I can not control myself when I see a young girl,'' newspapers quoted him as telling police. Since <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> confessed last week to murdering <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON>, an army of reporters has been stationed at his house, police headquarters, the victims' houses and murder sites. When questioned, teachers told reporters <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> seldom stood out and left little impression on them. Acquaintances described <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> as a quiet loner who bragged about his collection of nearly 4,500 videotapes, including many animated films. One of <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>'s videotapes, `` Chiniku no Hana'' -LRB- Flower of Blood and Flesh -RRB-, has a plot that resembles <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON>'s murder, investigators said. In it, a man follows a girl in his car, kidnaps her and then dismembers her in his apartment. Police quoted <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> as saying he picked up <PERSON> Mari </PERSON> in his car and `` drove her to a mountain, where I strangled her to death. I took two pictures of her in the car. I burned her with other things in the front yard at my house. I put her bones and ashes in a box and put it at the front door of <PERSON> Mari </PERSON>'s home.'' In February, when the box was found, letters were sent to <PERSON> Mari </PERSON>'s family and to the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> signed with the female name `` <PERSON> Yuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Imada </PERSON>. In the letters, the writer claimed to have killed <PERSON> Mari </PERSON> out of frustration from being unable to bear a child. Investigators said Monday they had discovered that `` <PERSON> Yuko </PERSON> <PERSON> Imada </PERSON>'' was the name of a female detective in a 1988 comic book who solved a case involving a poisoned salami in a supermarket. Police said they believe <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> wrote the letters because of his interest in comics and animated films. Police said <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> told them he had kidnapped <PERSON> Erika </PERSON>, strangled her in his car, stripped off her clothes and left her in a forest. <PERSON> Mitsuyoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Maniwa </PERSON>, a psychology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Shizuoka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> was unable to distinguish between reality and fiction because of his overwhelming interest in horror and animation videos. `` Through images and advertising, comic books, magazines and videotapes, men are taught to look at women as objects,'' said <PERSON> Chie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanematsu </PERSON>, editor of a newsletter published by <ORGANIZATION> Kodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suru </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Onnatachi </ORGANIZATION>, a group fighting exploitative images of women. `` This is the environment Japanese children grow up in.'' Under Japanese law, prosecutors have up to 20 days to release him or bring charges.
