 A suspect was charged with murder and kidnapping for allegedly beating a man in his home, abducting his wife and two small children and leaving the children near the women's body in a wooded area, police said. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Raynes </PERSON>, 21, was charged after turning himself in to police in <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, 110 miles north of <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>. He was flown to <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION> late Monday and was being held in the <LOCATION> Kennebec </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION> awaiting <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> arraignment today or Wednesday, state police spokesman <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. Authorities said family members identified the dead woman as Peg Shaw, 35. The state medical examiner's office scheduled an autopsy for Monday night, but the findings were not immediately available, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> identified her husband as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, who is employed at the <ORGANIZATION> Augusta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The couple's children _ son, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>, 3, and daughter, <PERSON> Julia </PERSON>, 1 _ were reunited with their father, police said. Police declined to say if <PERSON> Raynes </PERSON> knew the family or if any motive for the crime had been established. Before he turned himself in, police had put out an all-points bulletin for <PERSON> Raynes </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> refused to say whether there was any evidence in the <ORGANIZATION> Shaw </ORGANIZATION>'s home in the <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION> suburb of <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON> linking <PERSON> Raynes </PERSON> to the assault. <PERSON> Raynes </PERSON> has longstanding family ties in <LOCATION> Gardiner </LOCATION>, where he was living with his parents, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. He was employed by an electrical contractor in the <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION> area, he said. At about 6:30 a.m. Monday, an assailant entered the <ORGANIZATION> Shaw </ORGANIZATION>'s home, striking <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> in the head with a wooden mallet and handcuffing him in the basement, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. About an hour later, neighbors heard <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> screaming for help, he said. Police were called and as they were questioning <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, the family's van drove past the house, he said. `` We feel at that point that the suspect was alone,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. Police soon found the van abandoned at some railroad tracks in <LOCATION> Gardiner </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. Early in the afternoon, a state police trooper noticed some tracks coming from a muddy road in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gardiner </LOCATION>. Nearby, the trooper found the woman's body and her two children huddled together nearby. During the day, police used an airplane and boats on the <LOCATION> Kennebec </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in their search for the suspect, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said. Authorities also had set up roadblocks on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 201 in the area, <ORGANIZATION> Gardiner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said.
