<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Stage Strike; At Least 28 Killed This Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with strike beginning, more deaths.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, `The posters...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers drove public buses to get workers to offices today at the start of a daylong strike called by Sinhalese radicals protesting the continuing deployment of Indian troops in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. Shops in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> were closed and hundreds of employees began returning home because most offices and businesses were not functioning. Soliders in camouflage uniforms patrolled the city and policemen were posted at major intersections and near bus stops. At least seven people were killed by Sinhalese radicals today and Monday, according to military officials. The officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules, said the victims included two soldiers ambushed early today in the central town of <LOCATION> Nuwara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eliya </LOCATION>. The other killings were in the Sinhalese-dominated south, they said. The strike coincides with the 42nd anniversary of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> At least two Colombo-based newspapers refused to carry special supplements to mark the occasion, sources in the dailies said on condition of anonymity. The call for the strike came in posters signed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worker </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, which the government describes as a radical group. The posters in the Sinhalese language denounced the presence of an estimated 43,000 Indian soldiers, deployed in the northeast to oversee a 1987 peace accord aimed at ending a Tamil insurrection for an independent nation. The ultra-nationalist front says the Indian troops compromise the country's sovereignty. It also says the government has made too many concessions to the Tamil militants, who began their separatist campaign in 1983. The Tamils argue they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population. Tamils are 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> on June 1 asked <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to withdraw its soldiers, but so far <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has pulled out only 2,200 troops and the results have failed to appease the extremists. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has said a quick withdrawal of troops could lead to more violence but that it will withdraw soldiers in phases, pulling them all out by February. Sinhalese extremists have killed at least 4,000 people over the past two years, according to the government. About 11,000 other people have died in the 6-year-old Tamil revolt.
