<HEAD>Chinese Policewoman Executed for Taking Bribes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities have executed a policewoman in <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> for taking tens of thousands of dollars in bribes, official reports said today. Major state newspapers and television reports said the policewoman, <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayun </PERSON>, took bribes worth $ 56,150 in exchange for allowing people to remain in the southern city illegally. She was sentenced to death on June 19, but the reports did not say exactly when she was executed. Death sentences in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are usually carried out within a day or two with a bullet to the back of the head. In another report, the English-language <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said authorities had received 172,000 tips from informants at corruption reporting centers from January to June. The centers are part of a major government anti-corruption drive. The reports mentioned three pending cases of officials also accused of taking bribes. About 22,000 officials were accused of wrongdoing by the informants.
