<HEAD>President Touts Drug Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs of comment on revenue for drug fight after 3rd
graf, ``It is''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said today that the new drug-fighting strategy he will unveil next month is `` balanced, decisive, effective and achievable'' and said the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people demand no less. The president, at a news conference, called attention to a new Gallup poll that found overwhelming numbers of teen-agers think drugs are the biggest problem facing their generation. `` It is clear in these surveys that drug abuse is a national menace and that the central government must attack it with every means at its disposal,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Asked if he was willing to raise taxes to pay for the anti-drug fight, the president said, `` We're not going to have to, but we are going to expand federal expenditures.'' Asked where the money was coming, he said, `` Stay tuned, and we will show you in September how we're going to allocate the resources for this.'' The poll, released on Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said teen-agers and adults alike view drug abuse as the most important problem facing the country _ eclipsing fear of war, the economy, AIDS, crime, abortion and alcohol abuse as top concerns. The president gave no specifics of what the new strategy, to be released Sept. 5 after he returns from his vacation, will be. `` This will be a rather comprehensive national strategy,'' he said. `` There is a little bit of good news out there,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` There is a decline in the casual use of cocaine that's taking place.'' He said more can be done with education to counter the demand for drugs and that efforts to cut the supply line have also had some effect. One adult in four and one teen-ager in three has come to believe that drug abuse is the country's greatest problem, said the poll, and six in 10 teen-agers believe it is the greatest problem facing their generation. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, the national drug policy coordinator, said Monday that the poll results `` give a very clear sense of direction'' to the administration in its strategy. `` In times of crisis such as war, the public is willing to make great sacrifices to the public good,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallup </PERSON>. `` In key ways today, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are in a wartime mode and sense a national emergency in the drug crisis.'' Only six years ago, in a similar poll, unemployment most bothered 53 percent of adults; drugs and drug abuse did not register. Four years ago it was the top concern of only 2 percent. In the telephone conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in June and July it was the top worry of 27 percent. `` In the 50 years that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> public has been asked to name the most important problem facing the nation, it is virtually unprecedented for any social issue to appear at the top of the list,'' Gallup said. People are so disturbed, he said, that three-fourths of all teen-agers and nearly half of adults are ready to volunteer to help in drug prevention programs, education and treatment. `` A record number of Americans cite the drug crisis as the nation's top problem, replacing the ` guns and butter' issues of international tensions and economic worries,'' he told a news conference also attended by <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. After drugs and drug abuse the top concerns by adults were poverty, homelessness and hunger, 8 percent; the economy in general, 7 percent, and the federal budget deficit and the environment, 6 percent each. Next came crime, inflation, other economic problems, and a decline in morals, each with 3 percent; then abortion, unemployment, the trade deficit and dissatisfaction with government, at 2 percent, and quality of education, 1 percent. Twelve percent of adults listed other problems at the top, and the rest said they had no answer. Fear of war, the category listed the most worrisome by 27 percent of adults in 1985 and 23 percent in 1987, was listed first by only 4 percent in the new survey. Drug abuse was listed by 32 percent of teen-agers as the most important problem facing the country, ahead of fear of war, 14 percent; economic issues, 13 percent; environment and pollution, 7 percent; political issues, 6 percent; AIDS, 5 percent; crime, 3 percent; abortion, 2 percent; and alcohol abuse, 1 percent. Nine percent of the teen-agers listed other concerns and the rest said they did n't know. Gallup interviewed 1,005 adults and 500 teen-agers in the telephone poll, which had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points for the adults and 6 percentage points for the teen-agers. In the new survey, 60 percent of the teen-agers questioned said drug abuse is the biggest problem confronting their age group _ nearly twice the number saying it is the biggest problem for the country. For their age group, 13 percent said the worst problem was peer pressures, 11 percent said alcohol, and 8 percent said teen-age pregnancy. Considered the top problem by 3 percent or less: school problems, teen-age gangs, problems in growing up, unemployment, teen-age suicide, getting along with parents and career uncertainties. AIDS and fear of war were listed first by less than 1 percent.
</TEXT>
