<HEAD>South Korean Student Arrested After Return From North</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A South Korean student called `` the flower of unification'' by supporters returned home Tuesday from communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, clutching the hand of a clergyman who came to escort her. Both were arrested. Im Su-kyong, 20, went to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> six weeks ago as a symbol of the peninsula's reunification and had been told she would be arrested for violating a law against visiting an enemy country. Tears streamed down Miss Im's face Tuesday as she addressed a small crowd a few yards from from the demarcation line in the <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> truce zone. She said she was prepared for arrest. A South Korean soldier using a megaphone told her and the Rev. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyu-hyon </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic priest studying in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, to halt as they stepped over the raised cement line that bisects the oval-shaped <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> area. Miss Im dropped a bouquet of flowers she was carrying and grabbed <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>'s hand as they walked toward two South Korean border guards. The radical student left <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> capital, in a motorcade Monday, seen off by thousands of screaming people waving flowers. On Tuesday, what appeared to be much of the population of <LOCATION> Kaesong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, just outside the Demilitarized Zone, repeated the scene as her open limousine pulled away from a guesthouse and headed for the crossing. A loudspeaker van followed, blaring Miss Im's words of farewell. Just before crossing the line, she told the crowd: `` Reunification of our motherland will come in the near future if all Korean students <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and South struggle together. If there are forces that stand in my way, I will tell them of your sincere and peaceful desire for reunification.'' `` When our country is reunited, we will meet again!'' Miss Im shouted. A North Korean army officer, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Yun </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiun </PERSON>, said, `` She is brave.'' She, <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> and officials of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Peaceful </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reunification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comittee </ORGANIZATION> then linked arms and sang `` Our Wish Is Reunification,'' swaying from side to side. Several Westerners in the northern sector of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> were seen holding large placards that read `` <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is one.'' Officials in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> said Miss Im and <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> were the first people to cross the border against the wishes of either government since the Korean war ended in 1953. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> had said repeatedly that the crossing would violate the Korean Armistice Agreement. Officials of the U.S.-led <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, a signatory to the armistice, said they would file a formal protest with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> of the violation. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, consisting of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 15 other nations that supported <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in the 1950-53 war, has jurisdiction over the southern half of the <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> truce area 35 miles north of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. North Korean reports quoted Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Choi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ui </PERSON> <PERSON> Ung </PERSON>, chief delegate to the <ORGANIZATION> Armistice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, as saying: `` Allowing them to go to the South through <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> is in full accord with the armistice agreement and the spirit of humanitarianism.'' Miss Im, who studies French at <ORGANIZATION> Hankook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, entered <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on June 30 to attend the World Festival of Youth and Students in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. Her original plan was to return July 27, but she stopped short of the demarcation line when <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> refused permission, and went on a hunger strike for five days. North Korean officals said she became ill during the fast and had only recently been released from a hospital. <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in June and returned there after a trip to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where he studies with the Maryknoll Order in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. After their arrests, Miss Im and <PERSON> Moon </PERSON> were were flown to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> by helicopter and she was given a medical checkup before being turned over to the national intelligence agency, South Korean officials said. They said the priest was questioned about his trip and about anti-South <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> statements he allegedly made while in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. If the two are convicted under the national security laws, they could receive prison sentences of up to 10 years, legal experts said. In a speech in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> marking both <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s liberation from Japanese rule and its division in 1945, President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON> said the Koreas should `` recognize each other, seek coexistence and coprosperity and restore and develop a single national community through mutual opening-up, exchanges and cooperation.'' <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> also cautioned <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> against agitating radicals in the South. `` <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> must realize that the only thing they can gain by agitating the extremists and radicals within our society and by enticing a few of them to secretly visit <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> is the abhorrence of our people,'' he declared. Dialogue between the nations has been sporadic. Several meetings were held during the past year, but negotiations bogged down after the illegal trips to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
