<HEAD>Japan Remembers its War Dead on Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven thousand relatives of war victims paused for a minute of silence Tuesday on the anniversary of World War II's end, and Emperor <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> prayed for world peace. At least 10 members of the Cabinet of new Prime Minister <PERSON> Toshiki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> marked the day by making visiting the Shinto shrine for 2.4 million of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 3.1 million war dead _ including 14 convicted war criminals. <PERSON> Kaifu </PERSON> himself did not visit the Yasukuni Shrine. Opposition political parties and other groups in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> say such visits violate the constitutional separation of religion and state and promote militarism. <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>, attending a ceremony at a martial arts hall near the Imperial Palace, stood before 25,000 white and yellow chrysanthemums and bowed deeply, with Empress <PERSON> Michiko </PERSON> at his side. `` Looking back, it has already been 44 years since the end of the war, and in the midst of the peace and prosperity of today brought about by the untiring hard work of the people, when I recall the times replete with hardship, my mind is filled with a thousand emotions,'' <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> said. `` On the occasion of this day, in remembrance of the war victims, I think of the many people who lost their lives and of their families, and I am deeply saddened,'' he told relatives of war victims. `` I pray, along with all our people, for the future development of our country and for world peace,'' he said. The late Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>, <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON>'s father, announced to the nation on Aug. 15, 1945, that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would surrender to the allies. <PERSON> Akihito </PERSON> led Tuesday's ceremony in a minute of silence at noon, the exact moment that <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s voice was broadcast. About 90 members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANI