<HEAD>Crew Member from Crashed DC-10 Goes Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Records </PERSON>, the first officer of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 that crashed, killing 111 people, has been released from <ORGANIZATION> Marian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Records is the last of the crew of Flight 232 to leave the hospital. He flew home Monday to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state on a chartered Lear jet, said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Flight 232 attempted an emergency landing at <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gateway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on July 19 about 40 minutes after its No. 2 engine apparently exploded. Officials believe pieces of the disintegrating engine severed the aircraft's three hydraulic systems, making the jet almost impossible to steer. Pilot <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, 57, and second officer <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON> <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON>, 51, were released July 25 from <ORGANIZATION> Marian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. Pilot <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON>, 46, of <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, who helped guide the crippled airplane to the airport, was released from Aug. 5. <PERSON> Fitch </PERSON> was a passenger on Flight 232 but volunteered to help after the engine explosion. One hundred eighty-five of the 296 passengers aboard Flight 232 survived the crash. Six passengers remained in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hospitals Tuesday.
