<HEAD>Study: Early Infant Attention Saves Long-Term Care Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for improved pre-natal health care said Tuesday that spending $ 400 for expectant mother services can save a thousand times that amount in lifetime care costs for a low birthweight infant. Pointing out that the infant mortality rate in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the worst of any of the 18 industrialized nations, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to Prevent Infant Mortality called for `` universal access'' to early maternity and pediatric care for all mothers and infants. In a report issued this month, the commission said employers should make sure the health insurance they offer covers maternity and well-baby care, and called on the government to assume the responsibility for those who do n't have insurance. `` We can spend the money now or we can spend a lot more later,'' said the report. `` The costs of prenatal care _ care that can prevent low birthweight _ can be as little as $ 400 per mother. `` The lifetime costs of caring for a low birthweight infant can reach $ 400,000.'' Low birthweight is the leading cause of infant deaths and chronic and disabling illness, the commission said. <PERSON> Low </PERSON> birthweight babies are those born at less than five and a half pounds. `` This is very serious business,'' Dr. <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuckson </PERSON>, commissioner of health for the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. He said the infant mortality rate for blacks is twice that for whites and named the crack cocaine problem as the reason for a recent increase in infant deaths in the district. He and other panelists appeared for an infant mortality symposium sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professionals </ORGANIZATION> at the Capitol. The group acknowledged that a tight federal budget meant little money for pre-natal care programs, and <PERSON> Tuckson </PERSON> pointed out that much of the funding for public health concerns was now going to find a cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. But the panel said publicity could do a lot to get expectant mothers to available health care facilities.
