<HEAD>Once Docile Peasants Take on Active Role in Politics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the collapse of complete communist control of parliament, the once docile <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has emerged as an independent political force whose leaders seem determined to play a major role. Prime Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> said Monday he is ready to give up trying to form a government in favor of <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON>, the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON>, who has favored continuing his party's historical alliance with the <ORGANIZATION> communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, would be asked to create a Cabinet composed of representatives of all forces in parliament, according to <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>. But the 54-year-old economist, who has led the party since 1981 and was among top communist coalition candidates who were defeated in June parliamentary elections, faces opposition from Peasant lawmakers in parliament who fear reprisals at the polls if the party's links with the unpopular communists are not cut. Led by <PERSON> Aleksander </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentkowski </PERSON>, their independent-minded parliamentary floor leader, at least one third of the 76 Peasant deputies favor forming a coalition government with Solidarity. As the third-largest group in parliament, in which neither the larger communists or Solidarity lawmakers holds a majority, the Peasants suddenly have been catapulted into the role of kingmaker. The split between the party leadership and its representatives in parliament comes as the Peasants search for a new identity in response to voter disenchantment with the old party model and with an eye to completely free elections promised in the future. The peasant movement in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has deep roots, with the first organized Polish Peasant Party founded in <LOCATION> Rzeszow </LOCATION>, then in <LOCATION> Austria-ruled </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Galicia </LOCATION>, in 1895. <LOCATION> Rzeszow </LOCATION>, now in southeast <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, remains a center of rural activism. Before and after World War II, the party advocated land reform to free the peasantry from the control of large wealthy landowners. In pre-war <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, it was an important political force, with its leader <PERSON> Wincenty </PERSON> <PERSON> Witos </PERSON> serving as premier three times. One of its leaders, <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikolajczyk </PERSON>, also headed the Polish government-in-exile in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> during World War II. The Polish <ORGANIZATION> Peasants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> enjoyed a brief period of independent activity in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> after World War II. But the communist party that swept to power as a result of Soviet military might forced the merger of the independent party, known as the <ORGANIZATION> PSL </ORGANIZATION>, with a pro-communist <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the SL, in 1949 to form the ZSL _ as the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is now known. In that era of Stalinist purges, independent Peasant leaders were forced to flee the country, step down or bend to communist rule. In the most notorious case, <PERSON> Mikolajczyk </PERSON>, the wartime premier and only member of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> government to risk coming back to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> after the war to join a communist-led coalition, fled in 1947 when it became clear he was facing arrest and a show trial. He was denounced as a spy and lost his citizenship in 1949. Only this year was his citizenship restored posthumously by the Council of State. For most of the history of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ like the other minor party, the Democrats _ has obediently followed communist policy. In the last decade, as a result of political reforms, the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been allowed to develop a more independent policy while still acknowledging the communist party's `` leading role.'' It traditionally has exercised broad powers in rural areas and often holds the ministry of agriculture. The ZSL claims a membership of 500,000 and says it represents the interests of farmers. Peasant deputies resenting communist domination of the policies of their own party were critical of <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON>'s defense of continued obedience to the communists at a caucus last week. Deputies favoring a coalition with Solidarity also have said their constituents resented <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s election as prime minister because it left the impression that nothing has changed, despite Solidarity's victory at the polls in June. The internal revolt within the ZSL took on a new dimension Tuesday, as 120 peasant activists from around the country met in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and decided to resume the activities of <PERSON> Mikolajczyk </PERSON>'s old <ORGANIZATION> PSL </ORGANIZATION>, which was declared illegal in 1947, the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. Participants, who included representatives from <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION>, the independent farmers' union, said the party would be revived on the basis of the program adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> PSL </ORGANIZATION> in 1946.
