<HEAD>Child Murders Stir Concerns Over Violent Videos, Comics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN MOFFAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sun did n't shine into <PERSON> Tsutomu </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>'s room. The single window of the room where police believe <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> mutilated the body of 5-year-old <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> <PERSON> Nomoto </PERSON> was blocked by piles of comic books, pornography and children's cartoon videotapes. Police announced Tuesday that the 26-year-old print shop worker had confessed to killing and mutilating three girls in what television news is calling the worst murder case in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s postwar history. <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> was arrested Friday in connection with the killing of <PERSON> Ayako </PERSON> in June. Police said <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> also confessed to strangling <PERSON> Mari </PERSON> <PERSON> Konno </PERSON>, 4, in August 1988, burning the body and leaving it on her parents' doorstep; and strangling <PERSON> Erika </PERSON> <PERSON> Namba </PERSON>, also 4, in December and dumping her body on a mountain Television and newspaper coverage, including images of the suspect's room, has stirred fear in the homes of Japanese unfamiliar with the level of violent crime in many other societies. The child slayings are the latest in a series of murders of startling brutality by Japanese youth. Experts have been filling the airwaves with analyses of the impact of violent sex imagery that is perhaps more pervasive in Japanese popular culture than in any other developed country. Japanese barely blink at the graphic scenes of rape and murder they see in sports newspapers and comic books. They usually ignore the ads plastering telephone booths for prostitution services. Now, the extraordinary attention given the <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> case, which has dominated the front pages of national newspapers for days, has stunned the Japanese and stirred concern about sex and violence in the media. Police told local newspapers that the videos <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> collected ranged from cartoons to child pornography and violent movies. Authorities say <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON> confessed that in early June, he kidnapped the 5-year-old near her suburban apartment, killed her, mutilated her body and dumped it in a cemetery. Members of <PERSON> Miyazaki </PERSON>'s video club told newspapers he was an obsessive collector of cartoon tapes. His main hobbies, news reports say, were copying tapes and doing pornographic photography. His parents simply described him as shy. `` He was always so quiet that we wanted him to hurry up and get married so we could stop worrying about him,'' they told the <ORGANIZATION> Mainichi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. Some experts blame violent videos for contributing to his mental state and that of other people like him. `` If such videos were not so widely available, crimes like this might not have happened,'' said <PERSON> Susumu </PERSON> <PERSON> Oda </PERSON>, professor of mental health at <ORGANIZATION> Tsukuba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` For people with this kind of disposition, videos can help put plans in their heads.'' Another reportedly obsessive video hobbyist, <PERSON> Yoshiaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Kataoka </PERSON>, 21, was arrested Monday on suspicion of videotaping and sexually abusing more than 30 girls. <PERSON> Kozo </PERSON> <PERSON> Hida </PERSON>, a 22-year-old mechanic who reportedly spent most of his free time playing video games with neighborhood children, was arrested earlier this year on suspicion of strangling one of them. Gang violence also is worrying many Japanese. In June, a young man received the death sentence _ a rarity for a minor _ for his role in slaying a young couple out for a drive. A group of teen-agers beat the couple with iron rods, raped the woman, and killed both of them.
