<HEAD>Hills Urges Increased Personal Savings to Close Trade Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> on Tuesday expressed support for increasing tax benefits for individual savers, contending that expanded Individual Retirement Accounts would help boost the country's low savings rate and reduce <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s huge trade deficit <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> stressed that her endorsement did not mean that the administration had decided to propose such a change, which has the potential of benefiting millions of Americans. But other officials have said the administration is readying a fall campaign to address the chronically low <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings rate and that expanding tax benefits to individual investors who use IRAs was one of the ideas being considered. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said that expanding IRAs would `` highlight the great need for private savings to go up. It sends up a flag saying, this is very important, not only to your nation, but to your own future and to your children.'' One reason long advanced for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s high trade deficits is that Americans consume more than the country can produce domestically. If Americans could be persuaded to cut back on consumption and save more, then it would limit the need for foreign goods, economists reason. Higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings rates would also lower the cost of capital for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses and make their products more competitive on overseas markets. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said she did not know anyone in the administration who opposed increasing <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> tax benefits but she said there was concern over such questions as the potential loss of federal revenue. The huge cost to the treasury of IRAs was one reason that they were greatly scaled back by the 1986 Tax Reform Act. As a result, the number of tax returns claiming <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> deductions fell from 15.5 million in 1987 to 7.4 million last year. The administration is considering a variety of proposals to boost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings rates as part of a fall initiative designed to address long-range problems facing the country. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> is scheduled to kick off the campaign with a series of speeches, officials have said. The personal savings rate, savings as a percent of after-tax income fell to a 40-year low of 3.2 percent in 1987 and increased only slightly to 4.2 percent last year. By contrast, the savings rate in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was 16.5 percent in 1987. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said that increasing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> savings rate would help her answer charges from Japanese trade negotiators that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has not done enough on its own to solve its huge trade deficit. Currently, <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> is holding negotiations with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in an effort to get those nations to lower trade barriers cited by the administration last May when it issued a `` hit list'' of the countries with the most harmful barriers to sales of American products. The Japanese have countered that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> should make progress in boosting its savings rate and cutting its huge federal budget deficit as a way of lessening its dependence on foreign capital. The administration's various trade opening initiatives are aimed at lowering the country's huge trade deficit, which measured $ 126.5 billion last year on a current account basis covering trade in both merchandise and services. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said the current account deficit over the next 18 months may actually rise `` a little,'' reflecting the rise in the value of the dollar, which makes American goods less competitive on overseas markets. `` It is hard to predict, but I do not look for a dramatic drop in the trade deficit,'' she said.
