<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> called Tuesday for an emergency meeting of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s political leaders to seek `` rational solutions'' to a growing government crisis that he said threatens the nation's stability. The call was seconded by Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who also said that `` if society wants it,'' he would agree to serve as prime minister. If Solidarity succeeds in winning the prime minister's post, it would be the first non-communist government in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc since the late 1940s. Prime minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> said Monday he is ready to resign and abandon efforts to assemble a Cabinet in the face of Solidarity's opposition to any communist-led government. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> became prime minister 12 days ago. He urged that <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON>, a communist loyalist, be selected by <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> to form a `` grand coalition'' government that would include communists and members of Solidarity. But the proposal of <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON> drew little interest from other political groups, and <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON> himself by late Tuesday had not answered whether he wants to be considered a candidate. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> reiterated his proposal to form a government based on a coalition of Solidarity, the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, with some sensitive posts left to the communists. In the confused political situation, the state <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency said <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> `` expresses his concern over the deepening instability of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s political and economic situation.'' `` The president intends to appeal to representatives of the main political forces in the country for participation in a joint meeting devoted to seeking rational solutions ... as soon as possible,'' <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> also asked for restraint in `` political and social emotions, which make national accord more difficult.'' He contacted <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> through private channels to ask him for a meeting, possibly on Wednesday, said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Pusz </PERSON>. The joint meeting was likely to bring together representatives of the three parties and Solidarity, who were the main figures in last spring's successful talks that led to an accord on elections and legalizing the independent trade union movement after a seven-year ban. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he welcomed <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s decision to abandon forming a government but rejected <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON> as prime minister. He said the parties in the coalition discussions should decide on a candidate. `` If society wants it, I will have to go for the prime minister's office,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said `` But I would prefer someone else.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> also told state TV: `` After we sit down and reach agreement on deep reforms, then we will find the names -LRB- to head the government -RRB- too.'' He said any Solidarity-led government would guarantee the sensitive ministries of defense and interior to the communist party and would do nothing to endanger `` the functioning of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact'' military alliance. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said a Solidarity coalition would be `` a government of national responsibility, nominated with respect for the rights of the Polish president'' _ referring to the constitutional rights of <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> to control foreign policy and the armed forces. Despite such assurances, the prospect of a Solidarity-led government has alarmed the communist party and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which has said it could destabilize <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The party may also fear a Solidarity government would purge the `` nomenklatura'' _ party loyalists who hold tens of thousands of government and management posts _ and undermine the communist party's main base of support. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which along with the Peasants holds the parliamentary balance of power, on Tuesday endorsed <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s bid to form the next government. `` We think that we should do everything to realize <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s proposal, which has broad support,'' said the secretariat of the party, which historically has been allied to the communists <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said Aug. 7 that only a government headed by Solidarity and dominated by non-communists will have the credibility to solve <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s political and economic problems On the economic front, <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s caretaker <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> said extra food supplies are to be directed to larger cities, and publicly owned shops are to be sold or rented to private food vendors. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>'s decision to resign, saying it reflected a `` feeling of responsibility'' and could solve the government crisis. He said he had nothing personally against Gen. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, the interior minister for eight years. The resignation of a communist premier because the opposition wo n't endorse him _ as well as the bid by Solidarity to form a government against the wishes of the Polish and Soviet party authorities _ demonstrates how radically <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc politics have changed. The events would have been unthinkable a year ago. Cardinal <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>, the country's Roman Catholic primate, noted the changes during an annual Assumption Day sermon in <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION>. `` These events and changes of great significance were made finally without violence and destruction. ... And we should thank <PERSON> God </PERSON> for that,'' he said. But he warned the crowd of 150,000 of `` new concerns,'' including the economy. Solidarity began coalition talks Thursday with lamakers from the two minor parties, which have a combined strength of 103 seats and hold the balance of power in parliament. Normally obscure and once regarded as little more than communist fronts, the parties have been thrown into the role of kingmakers. <PERSON> Aleksander </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentkowski </PERSON>, the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s parliament delegation, said he favors Solidarity's concept for the next government About a third of the <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislators are leaning to Solidarity and want greater independence from the communists. <PERSON> Malinowski </PERSON> represents the more traditional, pro-communist wing of the party that claims 500,000 members. Since partially free elections in June, many of the minor-party lawmakers feel that in order to survive they must distance themselves from the generally unpopular communists.
