<HEAD>Ignition Test on Shuttle Rocket Motor Called Successful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Preliminary results show that an ignition test Tuesday of the space shuttle's redesigned solid rocket motor was a success, officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> said. The center is continuing to test the redesigned engine to check the performance of joints that were blamed for the 1986 Challenger explosion, even though the engine is currently used in flights. The lastest was by <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, which returned Sunday from a space voyage. The tested rocket motor contained intentional flaws, including a lack of adhesive on one of the joints and a small hole in another. But the test worked as predicted with no leaks passing expected points, said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Vibbart </PERSON>, project manager for the test. Further testing on the rocket motor will be done in the next few days to determine if any possible leaks occurred, officials said. The test was the initial one in the second phase of trials of the redesigned solid rocket motor. Officials expect to conduct several more years of testing, including some work on the next generation of rocket motors to be built at a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> site in <LOCATION> Iuka </LOCATION>, Miss. `` We feel that we have tested the redesigned rocket motor sufficiently to demonstrate its flight readiness,'' <PERSON> Vibbart </PERSON> said after Tuesday's test. `` But we're also cautious technical engineers that feel we need to continue to gather data to make sure there are no surprises lurking out there.''
