te speech. Police officials said security was strengthened after they received reports that nine militants had entered the capital for terrorist attacks. Sikh militants in the northern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> have been fighting for an independent nation since 1982. They have been blamed for 1,200 killings in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> this year and for bomb attacks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. Tuesday's violence, however, was blamed on Moslem militants who apparently were trying to enforce a general strike in the <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> state. Government spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pandit </PERSON> said 27 people were injured when a hand grenade exploded at a vegetable market in <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pandit </PERSON> said the grenade, thrown at a police jeep, missed and instead exploded among morning shoppers. He said no one was injured in three other bomb attacks around the area. <PERSON> Pandit </PERSON> blamed the attacks on `` Kashmiri militants and secessionists,'' which are terms used by the government to describe pro-Pakistani groups. <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>, a predominantly Moslem city, is about 62 miles west of the border with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which claims part of the state as its own. Three Moslem militant groups called the strike in <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION> to protest what they said was `` forcible occupation of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>.''
