Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, continued the fight against the Indian soldiers. A military official, who can not be identified under standing rules, said the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> ambushed and killed four Indian soldiers Tuesday in <LOCATION> Morawewa </LOCATION>, 145 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. At least 1,000 Indians have been killed since they arrived after the peace accord of July 29, 1987, and the Tamil war has cost 10,000 Sri Lankan lives since it began in 1983. The Indians are deployed only in the northeast, where most Tamils live, but the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> says their presence compromises Sri Lankan independence. It also claims the accord made too many concessions to Tamils. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s government blames the Sinhalese radicals for 4,000 killings since June 1987, including at least seven on Tuesday, which brought the total to 79 in four days. Tuesday's strike coincided with the 42nd anniversary of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> At least two <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> dailies refused to carry special supplements on the occasion, sources at the newspapers said privately. Tamils make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and claim discrimination by the majority Sinhalese. Most Tamils are Hindus and Sinhalese are predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, an overwhelmingly Hindu nation, became involved because it is the regional power and 60 million of its people are Tamils.
