 The prosecution in the tax evasion and extortion trial of hotel queen <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> rested its case Tuesday after six weeks of testimony in which former employees called her a penny-pinching tyrant. But even before the last witness had completed his testimony, attention was focused on the defense presentation. At issue is an accounting report that claims Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, are actually owed $ 681,000 in tax refunds during 1983-85, the years charged in the indictment. In arguments at the start of the day, Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> said defense attorneys had given him a copy of the report Monday afternoon. He complained to U.S. District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> that the rules of evidence mandate that the defense turn over such documents at a much earlier date. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, who appeared upset at the development, admonished Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Feffer </PERSON>. `` I am extremely disappointed in defense counsel for not furnishing this earlier,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` To me, it is inexcusable and I ca n't understand why it did n't happen.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said that if he allows the report to be admitted into evidence, the trial could take a month longer than expected because the government would need to rebut its conclusions. The judge also indicated that he may grant the government a delay to review the report and its underlying documents. If he does this, the trial could continue into September. He reserved his decision on whether to admit the report into evidence. The government `` needs to have absolute and complete disclosure of every aspect of this offer of proof,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` That includes finding out from the accountants when they were retained, what they had to say and what the basis is for their testimony.'' The report itself has not yet been made public. But <PERSON> Feffer </PERSON> and another lawyer for Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruton </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, have described it during arguments. They said two outside accounting firms reviewed the tax returns of several Helmsley-owned partnerships from 1983-85 and found that the accountants who prepared the returns had incorrectly calculated the depreciation of property. These alleged oversights, the lawyers claim, resulted in an overstatement of the Helmsleys' personal income. <PERSON> Bruton </PERSON> said the report concluded that the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> overpaid $ 90,000 in taxes in 1983, $ 13,000 in 1984 and $ 578,000 in 1985. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 69, is charged with evading about $ 1 million in federal taxes by charging about $ 4 million in personal expenses to Helmsley-owned businesses. Two former aides, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Licari </PERSON>, are being tried for assisting in the scheme. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Turco </PERSON> are additionally charged with conspiracy to extort payoffs and merchandise from vendors doing business with the <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> organization. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, 80, was also charged but was severed from the trial for health reasons. The last of 42 witnesses to testify was <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Lesnevich </PERSON>, a handwriting expert hired by the prosecution to review invoices, memorandums and other documents submitted during the trial. <PERSON> Lesnevich </PERSON> identified the initials and writing of Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> and her co-defendants on the documents. When <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> stood and said the government had rested its case, Mrs.