<HEAD>Jordan Schedules First Elections for Parliament in 22 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s first general parliamentary elections in 22 years will be held Nov. 8, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zeid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaker </PERSON> said Tuesday. His announcement, carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Jordan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said the date was set by the 26-member Cabinet in accordance with King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s election decree earlier this month. Interior Minister <PERSON> Salem </PERSON> <PERSON> Massadeh </PERSON> said about 1,400 candidates would run for a parliament of 80 seats and candidate registration would start Saturday. A ban on political parties, in effect since a coup attempt in 1957, remains in force so candidates will run as individuals although they can be members of political organizations. <PERSON> Massadeh </PERSON> said more than a million voters registered in a 15-day period that ended Tuesday. About 1.2 Jordanians are eligible to vote. He said committees would begin examining the registration lists Wednesday and the procedure would take a week. Since the early 1950s, parliaments have been evenly divided between the east and west banks of the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, but voting on both banks has not been possible since <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. A few district elections were held in 1984 to replace lawmakers who had died. King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> suspended the old 60-member parliament last year after relinquishing sovereignty over the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Election of the mew parliamewnt solely from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> will help seal the country's separation from the Israeli-occupied territory. The king approved a law April 17 calling for a 72-member body representing only the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. After four days of rioting over price increases later that month he promised elections by the end of the year. Political activists said the April election law did not distribute seats fairly according to population and it was amended in July to add eight seats for major population centers.
