<HEAD>Researchers Enlist Tiny Wasp in Lyme Disease Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wasp no bigger than the dot of an `` i'' could play a big role in the fight against Lyme disease following its rediscovery by a victim of the ailment who was searching through old newspaper files. The state on Tuesday awarded a $ 15,000 grant to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Amherst </LOCATION> to collect chalcid wasps, reproduce them and eventually let them loose on the deer tick that carries Lyme disease. `` There's very exciting possibilities there for some control of the problem that has really panicked some people who summer here,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON>, senior county agriculture agent for <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard and <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION> `` We need more information, but it looks like there's potential there,'' said <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Driesche </PERSON>, an entomology professor involved in the project. The minuscule wasp took on new prominence after a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Martha </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vineyard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lyme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` started to poke around in the Vineyard Gazette files,'' <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Engley </PERSON>, a 76-year-old <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard resident who had suffered two mild cases of Lyme disease, said he was trying to track down reports of an experiment he recalled from the 1920s. He found a 1937 article that reported a 1926 experiment in which chalcid wasps from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were released on the island to kill dog and wood ticks. That fit with a 1985 study that found the wasp's eggs had infested and were killing nearly 27 percent of the deer ticks on the island `` It's just a lucky break actually that it worked out that way,'' <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON> said. Local health officials then contacted the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Applied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> to explore the possibility of using the chalcid wasps for disease control. Lyme Disease, named for the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> town where it was first documented in 1975, can cause rashes, headaches and sore muscles, and, if not detected early, arthritis and heart irregularities. It can be treated with antibiotics. Between 5,000 and 8,000 cases of Lyme Disease are reported nationally each year, and 350 cases have been documented in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> since officials began documenting the disease in 1985, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Etkind </PERSON>, state epidemiologist. `` If this works, it could maybe reduce incidents by 35 percent,'' said <PERSON> August </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, commissioner of food and agriculture. `` That's 100 cases.'' The chalcid kills ticks by using a needle-like appendage to insert eggs inside the host. As the eggs develop, they kill the tick. The wasp also may help inhibit immature ticks from spreading the disease, health officials said. Researchers hope to begin work soon at a field station on <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Driesche </PERSON> said. If the wasps prove effective, state officials hope to have them commercially bred and used in conjunction with the current burning techniques and pesticides. `` It could be part of spring in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> would be releasing a box of these bugs,'' <PERSON> Schumacher </PERSON> said.
