<HEAD>Ex-Members of Disbanded Police Unit Confined to Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s administrator on Tuesday ordered that 1,200 policemen who had served in a paramilitary unit be confined to their bases for retraining. Adminstrator-general <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> said the policemen had been members of a disbanded counter-insurgency group known as `` <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION>,'' the Afrikaans-language word for `` crowbar.'' He said the action was designed to ease tensions as the territory, also known as <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, heads toward independence. <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> said the relative calm in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> allowed the policemen to be `` confined to bases where they will undergo reorientation and retraining to equip them for roles that are to be redefined.'' `` If the situation should in any way deteriorate ... I shall consider the steps that would need to be taken in order to restore law and order,'' he added. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> officials, including Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, had said that former <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> members were intimidating civilians in northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and should be removed from the 6,000-member Namibian police force. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> military and civilian personnel are in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> to monitor the transition to independence. The territory has been administered by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since World War I under a mandate from the defunct League of Nations. <ORGANIZATION> Koevoet </ORGANIZATION> squads played a leading role in the South African-led security forces battle against guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- SWAO -RRB-. Most Koevoet members were black Namibians. Some civilians accused the unit of brutality and atrocities. It was disbanded in January. Many ex-Koevoet members have been integrated into the regular police force. <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> had argued the ex-Koevoet fighters were needed to guard against possible attacks by <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas. Under a U.N.-backed regional peace accord, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to free the territory beginning April 1. But on that date, some 1,000 <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas crossed into northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> from southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, setting off three weeks of fighting that threatened to derail the independence plan. But the peace process is back on track and <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is favored to win pre-independence elections in November. <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON> said he decided to confine the ex-Koevoet members to the bases after <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials assured him that the threat of a <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> attack had subsided.
