<HEAD>Bush Says Anti-Drug Effort Will Get More Federal Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 17: ``Some law,'' with three grafs to note congressional
requirement and give Biden comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday promised a `` balanced, decisive, effective and achievable'' national drug plan, backed by more federal money, to meet Americans' demand for action. He declined to say where the money would come from `` because the final decisions have n't been made.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would not raise taxes, `` but we are going to expand federal expenditures.'' He added, `` We will have to do some reallocation of resources.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> focused on the anti-drug campaign on his last day at the White House before leaving for a three-week vacation in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. He told reporters at a news conference that his drug policy coordinator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has given him an outline of the developing national drug strategy. `` It's balanced, decisive, effective and achievable, and it will target all aspects of the problem. It will call for commitment and sacrifice and understanding, but it's clear to me that the American people demand no less,'' he said. He said final details of the plan will be worked out over the next several weeks before he announces the specifics on Sept. 5. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s proposal would target drug users, as well as strengthen enforcement. A draft of the plan obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> calls for users to be arrested and fined and to lose their driver's licenses, their cars, their federal grants if they have any <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> discussed whether to put federal financial muscle behind such proposals in a meeting Tuesday with his Domestic Policy Council of advisers. As drafted, the plan would withhold federal highway funds from states that did not revoke drug offenders' licenses, and it would withhold federal criminal justice funds from states that do n't perform drug tests on people in the criminal justice system Schools receiving federal money would have to have firm prevention programs. White House spokeswoman <PERSON> Alixe </PERSON> <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was still weighing those ideas. During his presidential campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supported revocation of drug offenders' driver's licenses. The draft strategy would seek a 49 percent increase in federal treatment money for 1990, to $ 925 million; $ 1.2 billion for new prison construction; a $ 200 million increase for state and local law enforcement, and $ 50 million for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, most of it for security improvements at public housing projects. The president, asked Tuesday if he planned to cut other programs to fund the anti-drug war, said he could not state where the money would come from, `` because the final decisions have n't been made. But we will have to do some reallocation of resources, there's no question about that.'' Pressed on how he would come up with the funds, he added,' ` We're in a period of hard times in the sense that we do n't have all the money that we would like to spend in several areas. At the same time he expressed determination to reduce the federal budget deficit and stay within the spending limits set by congressional budget writers. Some law enforcement professionals and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have criticized the anti-drug plan being developed by <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> under the legislation that established his job as too reliant on enforcement solutions. Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s resolve not to raise taxes to fight drugs. `` To make real progress on this issue, it is going to take a massive commitment of resources to law enforcement, drug treatment programs, drug education, and more. If that means raising taxes to pay for drug-fighting measures, so be it,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` We should not let the politics of ` read-my-lips' stand in the way of a full scale effort to arrest the drug epidemic.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday that his plan will lay out `` terms of accountability for all aspects of this problem, whether it's the treatment side or the education side or the law enforcement side, and we're holding ourselves accountable.'' `` We're saying in 10 years, there's going to be a lot less drug use,'' said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday met with two groups of community anti-drug activists to get their opinions on what must be done. Among them were the parents of a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> college student killed by members of a drug cult. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilroy </PERSON>, among about three dozen people meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, later said tougher enforcement is needed. Their son's body was found in a mass grave outside <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Drug treatment experts said after the meeting that they did n't dwell on where to get the money for the anti-drug fight <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I do n't know how the funds are going to be reallocated. But I know there is a total commitment to fight this war on drugs on all levels and, if there has to be some shuffling of resources, I'm certain they are astute enough to figure out exactly how to do that.'' The president, in his remarks, was asked if drug-producing countries should be penalized if they fail to cooperate in stemming the flow of drugs. `` I would n't be opposed to that, provided they were able to cooperate with us,'' the president said. But he said he has `` a certain responsibility to look at the problems that are facing some of these countries with limited armed forces of their own, with very complicated insurgencies in their countries and to formulate a foreign policy that takes these things into consideration.'' He expressed the view that <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s leadership wants to help, for example, but that its effort is hindered because <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> `` has been ripped asunder by the drug cartels,'' with many judges and officials assassinated.
