<HEAD>State Adopts Southern California Clean Air Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jananne is cq in 8th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL MONTE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State officials Tuesday approved a far-reaching blueprint to clear the polluted skies of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> so the state can meet federal standards by the year 2007. <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Wieder </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Supervisor serving on the nine-member <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, characterized the board's plan to clean the nation's smoggiest air as a `` leap into a ` Brave New World.''' `` But it's either that leap, or we wake up one morning and discover that it's ` The Day After,' and that we did it to ourselves,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilbray </PERSON>, a board member and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Supervisor. The board voted 8-0 to adopt the plan, despite industry opposition that prompted the board two months ago to request additional information from the regional agencies that developed the program. The plan was branded `` <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> justice'' by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON>, a commercial developer leading a coalition of business and labor interests battling to revise the smog cleanup effort. `` They're acting as their own judge, jury and executioner,'' <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> said. But while two reports were presented to clarify questions raised by business and political interests, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> made no changes in adopting the plan. `` Those people who oppose the plan are going to have to look at how they plan to accomplish the same goals,'' said ARB Chairwoman <PERSON> Jananne </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpless </PERSON>. `` So far, the alternatives offered have come up very short of the goals, or they do n't have any authority for doing what they want to do.'' The unprecedented plan represents a comprehensive approach to improving air quality, using land-use planning, transportation programs and stricter standards for industry smokestacks, automotive emissions and petroleum-based fuels. It was finalized last March, following more than five years in development, by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governments </ORGANIZATION>. The first part of the three-phase program calls for enacting more than 120 rules that would require, for example, the chemical reformulation of aerosol sprays and stricter controls on industry smokestacks. Existing smog-control rules were incorporated in the plan, but it also serves as a blueprint for the future by outlining the process for adopting new rules and by planning for the use of anti-pollution technologies yet to be perfected. The <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> basin has the worst air pollution in the nation, and has been working under a court order to comply with standards set by the federal Clean Air Act and enforced by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Air quality measurements for El Monte Tuesday showed ozone levels at about 15 hundred parts per million, an unhealthy level, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichhorn </PERSON>, a spokesman for the South Coast Air Quality Management District. `` It was unhealthful, but for August in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> it was pretty good,'' <PERSON> Eichhorn </PERSON> said. Following the board action, state and two regional agencies can begin enacting the plan's clean air provisions, even though the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has yet to give its approval, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessa </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> is the only state with its own standards for vehicle emissions, and has led the nation in reducing smog by pioneering new standards and such devices as the catalytic converter, <PERSON> Sessa </PERSON> said. Last June, for example, the board tightened its emission standards, which exceed federal standards for several pollutants, for automobiles to be produced in 1993 and afterward. The board also plans to require improvements in computerized pollutant control equipment in cars, tighten state smog check requirements and set new standards for petroleum-based fuels. <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> refused to say whether his group, the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, plans to file a legal challenge to the plan, although he said that's an option to be considered.
