<HEAD>Remains of 5 Suspected Victims of Cannibal Reburied</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd cq in lede</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bones of the five suspected victims of cannibal <PERSON> Alferd </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> were reburied Tuesday in a simple yellow pine coffin as a minister prayed for all victims of `` crime and evil.'' In a ceremony devoid of flowers or music, the scientists who dug up the bones last month placed them in five compartments inside the 4-foot-by-4-foot corduroy-lined coffin. Four <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> clergymen spoke briefly to a crowd of about 150 gathered at the hilltop grave before the coffin was lowered 8 feet into the ground. A steel plate was placed over the coffin to discourage vandals. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> was the only survivor of a snowbound party of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> gold-seekers that was trapped in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> in southwest <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> during the winter of 1874. <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> claimed one member of the party killed the other four and <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> was forced to kill him in self-defense. He said he ate their remains to survive. He eventually was convicted of manslaughter and served time in prison, but maintained his innocence until his death. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor who wanted to separate fact from legend about <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>, led a research team that dug up the bones last month. The bones and other artifacts found in the common grave were transported to the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> for analysis. But time and money shortages forced the reburial of the bones earlier than the scientists had hoped. Last week, <PERSON> Starrs </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON>, curator of physical anthropology at the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, said they found at least four of the victims were bludgeoned to death in butcher fashion and then were carefully defleshed. They also said there was no visible evidence that any had suffered gunshot wounds. <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON> said Tuesday that the only answer scientists found in their examination of the remains was that the victims were murdered and cannibalized. `` We found nothing to corroborate or refute anything <PERSON> Packer </PERSON> said,'' <PERSON> Birkby </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` We'll never know who did it based on any solid physical evidence. We're never going to know.'' When the bones were dug up in July, the expedition took on the air of a light-hearted historical circus. Reporters descended on the community and T-shirts with slogans such as `` have a friend for dinner'' and `` taste the high country'' sold briskly. On Tuesday, the Rev. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Light </PERSON> of the Presbyterian Community Church began the reburial ceremony with a prayer for victims of `` crime and evil.'' Three other ministers, representing the other religious communities of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, population about 400, addressed the gathering of local residents and tourists. Then the scientists placed the bones in the coffin compartments and served as pall-bearers. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarman </PERSON>, who owns the property on which the remains were buried, placed five grapevines and eucalyptus leaves on the coffin before it was lowered into the common grave. Dressed in a black jogging suit and black tennis shoes, <PERSON> Jarman </PERSON> said she's pleased the bones have been returned to the place where they were dumped in burlap sacks 115 years ago. `` They've become my little friends,'' she said. A headstone erected on the site in 1928 or 1929 was to be restored to its place and the site opened to tourists Wednesday.
