<HEAD>Greek Cypriots March to Protest Turkish Occupation of Famagusta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHERENIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 3,000 Greek Cypriots holding lighted candles marched Tuesday to the U.N.-policed Green Line to protest the Turkish occupation of Famagusta, once a flourishing tourist resort. The Green Line divides the island into <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> and Turkish Cypriot zones. The marchers, led by <PERSON> Famagusta </PERSON>'s former Mayor <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Voyatzis </PERSON>, walked through <LOCATION> Dherenia </LOCATION>, a suburb of the now-deserted port city, to a checkpoint. There they handed a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officer a petition calling for Greek Cypriot refugees to be allowed to return home. `` Greeks and Turks must live together,'' the demonstrators shouted. The demonstration marked the day in 1974 that Turkish troops seized Famagusta after invading <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. The Turks invaded after a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking to unite the island with with <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Before the march, a message from President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cypriot </LOCATION> leader, was read, saying `` We reiterate our determination to return to our homes in the Turkish-occupied north, but we are trying to achieve this through peaceful means.'' <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON> referred to U.N.-sponsored talks being conducted with Turkish Cypriot leader <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON> aimed at reunifying the island as a two-zone federated state. The Green Line that splits the island is guarded by a 2,300-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping force that has served in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> since violence flared in 1963.
