<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gay Men's Health Crisis on Tuesday urged New Yorkers who may have AIDS to seriously consider being tested for the disease, a change of emphasis that the group said was based on medical and political developments. While the organization has been skeptical about testing in the past, its director, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON>, said it was reassured by a state confidentiality law and encouraged by evidence some drugs can extend the lives of AIDS patients. `` We've always said think about it,'' said <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON>. `` The difference is that if you thought about it in 1985 you probably would n't want to get tested. If you think about it in 1989, you probably will want to get tested.'' The organization was not recommending the test be taken, <PERSON> Dunne </PERSON> said, because the decision was a personal one. <ORGANIZATION> GMHC </ORGANIZATION> placed ads headlined, `` Think about it,'' in the city's four major daily newspapers Tuesday. They noted that the drug AZT can slow development of acquired immune deficiency syndrome and treatments such as aerosolized pentamidine can prevent some AIDS-related illnesses. <ORGANIZATION> GMHC </ORGANIZATION> provides counseling for people with AIDS and lobbies in their behalf.
