<HEAD>Valdez Moving Into Drydock For Nine Months Of Repairs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK EVJE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shipyard workers on Tuesday began moving the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> from a pier to a dock where the tanker that caused the nation's worst oil spill will be repaired over the next nine months. Tugboats helped guide the 987-foot ship into the repair dock, which is only 3 feet wider than the 166-foot-wide Valdez, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> officials said. Workers plannd to tow the Valdez from its current berth at a <ORGANIZATION> NASSCO </ORGANIZATION> pier into <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, then turn and back it stern-first into the dock. The vessel was launched three years ago from the same dock, which resembles a huge swimming pool separated from the bay by a moveable gate. The crippled ship was returned to <ORGANIZATION> NASSCO </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, where it ran aground March 24 in <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION>, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of crude into the sound's wildlife-rich waters. Repairs to the ship and its shredded hull were expected to cost about $ 25 million. Dockmaster <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, a veteran of more than 40 dockings, said he would use up to eight tugs to coordinate the ship's movement while monitoring the tanker's position through a team of divers and surveying instruments. Shipyard workers were not expected to start repairs this week because it will take about six days to remove all the water from the dock. `` I suspect there will be a two-week period in which the only people in there will be lawyers and engineers,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NASSCO </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutter </PERSON>. Once inside, the gate will be closed and <ORGANIZATION> NAASCO </ORGANIZATION> crews will start draining water from the repair dock. After lowering the water level about six feet, which takes about four hours, the <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> will come to rest on blocks and supports that will hold the ship while it's being repaired Five clusters of 24 adjustable jacks, each having a 250-ton capacity, have been installed to maintain an even keel when the ship is lowered. A level landing was crucial because the tanker otherwise might slide off the blocks and damage itself and the repair dock, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they plan to return the tanker to service, though possibly under a different name, after repairs are completed. The <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> arrived off the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> coast July 10 after being towed more than 2,000 miles from Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. But its entry into the bay was delayed three weeks after oil slicks were sighted near the vessel. The ship pulled into the NASSCO yard on July 31.
