<HEAD>$Adv 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs, Aug. 17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Unsung Hero of Opera</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If there can be an unsung hero in opera, especially in a monumental extravaganza such as `` Die Meistersinger von <LOCATION> Nuremberg </LOCATION>,'' it would have to be the chorus master. Despite the central role of the 97 singers, the largest chorus in any <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> production to date, the man charged with welding them into a crisp ensemble with flawless diction and perfect pitch gets no major billing and takes no bows. What <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiore </PERSON> does take is unabashed pride in his work. `` I'm always in charge, because I have to be,'' he said. `` I get very good results with the chorus.'' In an interview at a rehearsal earlier this month, <PERSON> Fiore </PERSON> waxed enthusiastic during a parade scene that brings more than 100 people on stage in the third act. `` You see that? Active, energetic. They really are the populace, not just 100 sticks, people singing notes,'' he said. The 63-year-old <PERSON> Fiore </PERSON> became chorus master five years ago after occasional work as associate chorus master, coach for principal singers and other jobs with the opera dating to 1968. `` I brought him in,'' said <PERSON> Speight </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, general director of the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't think there's a better chorus master in the country.'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, who spent two years as host of the television series `` Live From the Met'' and eight as music critic for the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Fiore </PERSON>'s crowning achievement was a fight scene with 135 people on stage in the second act. `` For three minutes they are in a wild melee, singing and fighting on stage. Then the night watchman's horn is heard, and everyone vanishes,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. The libretto calls for 16 separate vocal lines _ for example, four soprano sections _ each exchanging epithets. In previous modern stagings, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said, `` they simply have each line of people sing all the words.'' Director <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Rochaix </PERSON>, however, decided that to be true to <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s libretto, half the singers in each line should sing one epithet and the other half the response. `` People are going to hear a difference, a clarity of lines, I hope,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> has done such extraordinary work that the people are able to do this. He taught it to them -LRB- to sing -RRB- faster than he ever thought <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> -RRB- could conduct it.'' With the slightest breakdown in timing, anything less than perfect pitch and diction, the music would sink into cacophany. `` I think we've rehearsed that fight scene 30 or 40 times. It has n't fallen apart yet,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` Die Meistersinger,'' one of the longest operas at six housrs, poses other challenges as well. Total costs are likely to exceed $ 1.6 million for seven performances Aug. 3-19. `` A -LRB- new -RRB- production on the scale of ours has not been done since the Met's -LRB- The Metropolitan Opera -RRB- in 1962,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` Everybody likes to do ` Die Meistersinger.' It's just that they ca n't afford to produce it.'' A quarter or more of the cost goes for costumes, sets and other one-time expenses. Under a contract with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Musical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION>, full-time choristers get $ 8 an hour for rehearsal time, plus a performance fee, for a total of about $ 1,200 for `` Die Meistersinger,'' while auxiliaries earn as little as about $ 100 total, said <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, a soprano in the chorus since the company was founded 25 years ago. `` They all have jobs like anybody else,'' <PERSON> Fiore </PERSON> said. ` Some of them are housewives, of course, but that's a full-time job, too.'' Regulars, including those from past seasons, must survive an audition every two years. About 190 singers were heard in special auditions to choose the 61 auxiliary choristers in `` Die Meistersinger.'' The chorus, which began rehearsals May 18, sings the opening and closing lyrics, and `` Die Meistersinger'' is one of handful of operas in which `` the people'' comprise a central role. `` <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> composed this opera as a strong statement of the German people,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` In each of the acts, the people have a very strong role to play.'' Set in 16th-century Nuremberg, the opera tells the story of <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, a cobbler and master singer who winds up serving as principal judge in a song contest among the town's apprentice master singers. To the victor goes the hand and fortune of <PERSON> Eva </PERSON>, the beautiful daughter of the town's wealthy <PERSON> goldsmith </PERSON> and the object of <ORGANIZATION> Sach </ORGANIZATION>'s own unrequited love The cast includes <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Roloff </PERSON> as <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, soprano <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Donath </PERSON> as <PERSON> Eva </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, <PERSON> Benn </PERSON> <PERSON> Heppner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bergitta </PERSON> <PERSON> Svenden </PERSON> in other lead roles. `` Die Meistersinger'' is the seventh new <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> production for <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>. Since he took over in 1983, the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> has risen to No. 6 in attendance nationwide, and <ORGANIZATION> Wagner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> has declared it `` without a doubt the leading <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> company in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The company is best known for annual stagings of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s four-part `` Der Ring des Niebelungen'' from 1975 to 1987, the first nine years in English as well as German <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, hired largely to overhaul the Ring, presided over new productions of `` Die Walkure'' in 1985 and of `` Das Rheingold,'' `` Siegfried'' and `` Die Gotterdammerung'' in 1986. Despite the company's overall financial health, annual productions ended in 1988 because of persistent operating deficits for the $ 3.5 million summer extravaganza and what <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> saw as a lack of sufficient local corporate and individual donations. He has said he hopes to revive the Ring for performances every two or three years, starting in 1991. The Ring's legacy is evidence this year with the return of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> as conducter, <PERSON> Rochaix </PERSON> as director, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> as lighting director and soloists <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roloff </PERSON>, who sang <PERSON> Wotan </PERSON> in 1984, 1986 and 1987.
