<HEAD>Thai Villagers Caught in War Not Their Own</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 BAN NON SAO-AE, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The war has nothing to do with them, but without warning it comes roaring in often on the 729 people of Ban Non Sao-Ae who make their living by farming. The war is <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s _ government forces fighting rebels _ and the villagers have the misfortune of living close to the border where the fighting frequently breaks out with artillery barrages that send shells crashing into <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. `` Bunker'' is one of the few English words that have worked their where also.'' <PERSON> Dum </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankeja </PERSON>, 64, said he also will stay. <PERSON> Dum </PERSON> and his wife share a bunker with three other households, and he said adversity has brought the villagers closer. `` We have to go through this together. We help each other out. If we go into the bunker, we go in together.'' Less fortunate was <PERSON> Somwang </PERSON> <PERSON> Janpit </PERSON>, 22, one of at least three villagers who recently lost legs to landmines. In June, he was searching for bamboo shoots in a deserted field. He thought the blast he heard was someone shooting birds _ until he saw his right leg was gone. `` Yes, I'm angry,'' he said. `` Now I ca n't take care of my father and mother.'' His mother, 63, now toils nine hours a day in the fields to feed him, his handicapped sister and their father, 84. At the village school, anything that sounds like gunfire sends the children dashing for the bunker on the compound. Heavy shelling last year shattered several school buildings. But most students have learned to cope, a teacher said. `` Their homes are here in the village. When they hear it -LRB- the shelling -RRB-, they are scared. When it's over, they go and play like children everywhere.''
