<HEAD>Rates Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in several weeks. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.2 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.01 percent, up from 7.94 percent last week. Another $ 7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.83 percent, up from 7.70 percent last week. The rates were the highest since three-month bills sold for 8.09 percent on July 24 and six-month bills averaged 8.08 percent on June 19. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 8.29 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,797.50 and 8.26 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,604.20. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 8.12 percent last week, up from 7.73 percent the previous week.
