<FIRST>r f PM-EconomicOutlook     08-15 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economic Outlook,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists Predict Slow Growth for Rest of '89, Improvements in '90</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fed Attack, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s tight-money policy, initiated last year to slow the economy and prevent inflation, has achieved its desired effect, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> economic research shows. An economic forecast prepared for release today predicts a `` soft landing'' following the implementation of the policy and 3 percent growth during 1990 with an unemployment rate of 5.7 percent. The forecast is based on a series of equations involving hundreds of economic variables that comprise the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Quarterly Econometric Model of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Economy, also known as the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Model. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> economist who helped prepare the forecast with Professor <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hymans </PERSON> and economist <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crary </PERSON>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s policy in part caused economic growth to slow this year. `` The danger that runs in this type of policy is if the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> tightens too much ... growth might slow down or become negative, and that would be a recession,'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said. She said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>'s most recent measurement showed that the economy is growing at a rate of 1.7 percent this year. The forecast indicates continued sluggishness but a pickup during 1990. `` While we expect slow growth for the remainder of this year ... we do not expect a recession,'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said. `` We expect renewed growth during 1990. That is contingent upon easing of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> toward the end of this year.'' According to the forecast, inflation is expected to hold steady at 4.4 percent in 1989 and 1990, then creep up to 4.5 percent in 1991. The gross national product will grow by 2.6 percent in 1989, 2.2 percent in 1990 and 2.9 percent in 1991, according to the forecast. Civilian unemployment is forecast to edge up from 5.3 percent in 1989 to 5.7 percent in 1990 and 5.8 percent in 1991. Automobile sales are predicted to hold steady at 10 million per year through the forecast period, a decline from the 10.6 million units sold in 1988. Housing starts are expected to rebound from 1.4 million units in 1989 to 1.7 million units in 1991.
</TEXT>
