<HEAD>Richard C. Breeden: Lawyer, Banking Specialist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SEC-Breeden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When you ask people about <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, the savvy <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer nominated to head the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, they always start off by calling him `` very intelligent'' or `` extremely bright.'' `` He has the experienced, good mind that will stand him in good stead,'' former <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Roderick </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said Monday after the nomination of <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, an architect of the savings and loan industry bailout, was announced. Even people who question the wisdom of the appointment, like Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>, start their criticism with `` Mr. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> is highly intelligent and did fine work on the S & amp; L reform package ...'' One industry source, who did not wish to be identified, said that because of his keen mind <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> does not `` suffer fools gladly'' and could be abrasive. But when <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> was gathering information for a task force chaired by then-Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, on what financial regulatory rules needed to be amended or scrapped, said the source, `` We sent him some very difficult, complicated stuff. `` Usually, people in that position read it and do n't understand it or pass it on to someone else to read it. But when we met with him it was obvious he had read it and understood it all.'' Industry observers believe <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>'s wide-ranging experience will be an asset in the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> position. `` He comes to this job with a fairly broad knowledge of the financial services industry,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardiman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees over-the-counter stock trading. A 1972 graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and a 1975 graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> practiced securities law on Wall Street with the prestigious firm <ORGANIZATION> Cravath </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. He also worked for the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office of the politically powerful <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law firm <ORGANIZATION> Baker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Botts </ORGANIZATION>. From 1981-82, <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> was an executive assistant to the undersecretary of labor. `` He's been a practitioner. He's been in government. He knows banking,'' said the industry source. `` He may get rid of a lot of junk along the way but he'll be doing his job.'' The White House announcement ended months of speculation about who would succeed departing <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> who announced in May he was stepping down. In contrast to <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON>, 60, an academic and legal expert who managed to keep his distance from the free-market philosophy of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, 39, is known as a fierce fighter for the policies of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> helped write the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan for bailing out the nation's ailing savings and loan industry and then shepherded through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the plan to spend more than $ 150 billion over three decades to deal with the nation's biggest money problem since the Depression Before that, <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, native who now lives in the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> suburbs outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, worked for and with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in a number of capacities. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, now a presidential assistant for issues analysis, also helped fashion administration policy in dealing with the Exxon Valdez oil spill. He helped candidate <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> prepare for the 1988 presidential debates with <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. From 1982 to 1985, he was deputy counsel to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as vice president. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> also served as staff director on the task force <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> chaired to reform the financial regulatory system. `` I'm not sure if he's a regulator or a deregulator,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Macklin </PERSON>, chief executive officer of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> investment banking firm of <ORGANIZATION> Hambrecht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quist </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Macklin </PERSON>, who has known <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> since 1984, said the wiry and intense lawyer is `` interested in efficient, cost effective regulation. He knows the inter-relationships in the world of financial services, he has a broad view of what's out there and an extensive knowledge.''
