<HEAD>Weather Service's 30-day Forecast Boosts Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and soybean futures opened higher today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> after getting a boost from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s 30-day forecast. The forecast issued Monday called for below-normal precipit ` tion and above-norlal temperatures in major crop areas. An <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that noted some detdrioration in soybean crop quality may have contributed to today's early gains. Analysts said the good showing in the soybean and corn pits should spill over into the wheat market. Wheat also should get support from <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s bid for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat under the export bonus program, which subsidizds grain sales to foreign nations, the analysts said. In early trading, wheat was a -LCB- cent to 2 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.99 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 3 \ cents higher with September at $ 2.31 a bushel; oats were -RCB- cent to 2 cents higher with September at $ 1.38 a bushel; soybeans were 3 -LCB- cents to 11 -LCB- cents higher with August at $ 6.14 a bushel Livestock and pork futures were lower in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .05 cent to .23 cent lower with August at 74.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .27 cent lower with August at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent to .37 cent lower with August at 47.07 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .40 cent to .60 cent a pound with August at 24.75 cents a pound. Livestock futures settled mostly lower and pork futures were mixed in Monday's trading.
