<HEAD>Central Bank Not Likely to Lower Interest Rates: Economists</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 6th and 7th grafs pvs with 4 new grafs to add Bush comments,
picks up 8th graf pvs, ``Private economists...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> is n't likely to lower interest rates any time soon to boost economic growth, despite a pointed warning of recession from President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget director, many economists say. Analysts predicted Monday that interest rates will hold steady because the central bank is satisfied it has done all it needs to keep the country out of an economic slump. Those economists suggested that comments by Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> might actually backfire and make the central bank less inclined to ease credit conditions for fear of appearing to bow to political pressure. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> complained that the central bank was keeping interest rates too high and would shoulder the blame if the country falls into a recession. `` If we do have a recession, I think it will be because they erred on the side of caution'' in fighting inflation by keeping interest rates too high, <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said Sunday on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Meet the Press.'' The White House tried to soften the sting from <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>'s message by praising the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> on Monday for generally doing a `` good job'' but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today generally endorsed the comments during a morning press conference. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> for expressing his views, which he called `` very balanced.'' `` I feel very comfortable with his -LRB- <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>'s -RRB- sallying forth,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` I think I have said the same things in the past.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he did not know of any president who had ever come out against lower interest rates, but he stopped short of saying that he believed that if a recession did occur, it would be the fault of the central bank. Private economists were surprised by the timing of <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>'s criticism, given recent economic statistics such as a drop in the jobless rate in August that suggest the economy is n't as sluggish as previously feared `` There is virtually no chance that we will have a recession this year. So why stir up this fuss and get financial markets unsettled when you do n't have to?'' asked <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, head of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> forecasting company. But other economists said they believed <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> was positioning the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to take the blame if the economy does weaken and the country ends up in a recession right before next year's congressional elections. `` This is a classic situation of setting up the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to be the fall guy if something goes wrong,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, chief economist at <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> and other economists said it was unlikely that <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>'s remarks would have any impact on upcoming <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> decisions <ORGANIZATION> Top </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policymakers will meet again in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Aug. 22. Many economists said they expected the central bank to hold interest rates steady and not ease further given recent signs that certain key sectors, such as consumer spending, are rebounding. `` So long as the economy is OK, there is no reason for the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to ease any more,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. From March 1988 through March 1989, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> pushed short-term interest rates higher in an anti-inflation campaign The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> reversed course in June and has made three modest moves to lower interest rates by making more money available to the banking system. Banks have been able to cut their prime lending rate since early June by a full percentage point to 10.5 percent. Home mortgage rates have declined as well, dropping below 10 percent to stand at 9.96 percent for fixed-rate loans. <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> said he believed mortgage rates have hit their low for the year and may even climb by about one-fourth percentage point in coming weeks as financial markets realize that the central bank has decided to hold off on further easing moves. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Getman </PERSON>, senior economist at the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, consulting company, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> was correct to pause before driving interest rates any lower. He said if economic activity turns out to be stronger in the second half of the year than forecast, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> would run the risk of triggering higher inflation next year by loosening credit conditions too rapidly.
</TEXT>
