 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said today tentative prices for its 1990 cars will increase an average of 5 percent over comparably equipped 1989 models. Nearly half the boost is caused by the installation of driver-side air bags in all of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s U.S.-made cars, expected to be about 1 million vehicles in the 1990 model year, spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said. She said the average air bag will cost a consumer $ 450, less than what <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> pays to buy and install them. She refused to say exactly what the automaker is spending on the systems. The rest of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s price increase stems from economic reasons, including higher material and labor costs, she said. The federal government requires driver-side air bags or automatic seat belts on all cars made in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after Sept. 1. Earlier this month, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced a tentative average price increase of 3.4 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its car prices could go up as much as 4.8 percent for the coming model year. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said a few of the 1990-model cars offered by the nation's No 3 automaker will decrease in price while the rest will increase between 2.8 percent and 6.9 percent. She said she did not have a list of all models and their price increases. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s final retail prices will be announced in September or October, she said.
