 Software maker <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it would lay off at least 15 percent of its employees, or about 260 workers, and cut other costs in the face of expected additional losses. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION> reported a $ 19.8 million second-quarter net loss on revenue of $ 59.5 million. Its president and chief operating officer, <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, resigned and his duties were assumed by board chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Esber </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` The -LRB- workforce -RRB- reduction will be a minimum of 15 percent,'' according to <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Duttenhayer </PERSON>, who said the company now has 1,731 employees worldwide. <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION>, once a top manufacturer of computer software, recently has faced intense competition in its core business of software for the storage and retrieval of information in personal computers. It said reduced revenues, together with anticipated job-cutting costs and other expenses, may result in a larger operating loss for the third quarter, which ends Sept. 30, than in the second quarter that ended June 30. The company said its previously announced program to reduce inventories on the shelves of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> distributors and resellers is continuing. <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION> also is going through a transition to a newer version of its dBASE IV software, and said shipments of the current version are expected to decline as customers wait for the new version. <PERSON> Esber </PERSON> said he will directly oversee the database business. `` This is another important step in restoring <ORGANIZATION> Ashton-Tate </ORGANIZATION>'s profitability,'' <PERSON> Esber </PERSON> said `` The company's cost-reduction program will result in greater focus and execution on projects with the biggest impact on near-term revenues.''
