<HEAD>Workers Retake Assembly Plants Closed By Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYNOSA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of workers tore down black and red strike flags, unlocked gates and poured back to their jobs Tuesday at American-owned assembly plants closed over a union power struggle. `` We're waiting for the other union to come and try to take us out,'' said <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Torre </PERSON>, 22, an assembly line worker at the Nibco valve plant in this northern border city. `` We've been inactive for three weeks. We need our jobs,'' said <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Becerra </PERSON>, a Nibco section chief. Maquiladoras are foreign-owned plants that take advantage of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s lower wage rates to assemble products to sell in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. About 900 workers, both men and women, defied a rival union and, unlocking gates, reopened 15 American plants closed July 25 when one union leader attempted to take control from another. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> put up strike banners and locked the gates of plants organized under leader <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>. About 2,000 workers were idled by the strike, although they said the companies continued to pay their salaries. <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> no longer could legally represent the workers because <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> had withdrawn from the Federation of Mexican Laborers, or CTM. But the workers said Tuesday that they want <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> as their union leader whether or not he's allied with the CTM. They're tired, they said, of waiting for government and judicial authorities to end the strike. `` We want the government to intervene. We want them to respect the contract we have with <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Aurelio </PERSON> <PERSON> Veraza </PERSON>, a Nibco supervisor. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, who had called for workers to return to their jobs, said Tuesday that he did so because `` they do n't have any reason to stay out.'' <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> was not immediately available for comment. No American manager was on the premises of any of the plants as the workers calmly walked past the two or three guards at each gate. Once inside, each person went to work at his or her station, taking orders only from the supervisors involved in the retaking of the plants. The workers contend that <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> acted illegally when he forced the plants closed. `` Only workers have the right to strike,'' said <PERSON> Veraza </PERSON>. `` We're happy with the work the Americans give us They're giving us chances to advance.'' The state labor arbitration board had ruled in favor of <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>, but the plants took the case to federal court asking that <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> be declared the official representative. The federal court has yet to issue a ruling in the case. All the workers interviewed said they expected <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> supporters to attempt to remove them from the plants. No action had been taken by the rival union, however, hours after the plants reopened. Two American companies, <ORGANIZATION> Invacare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Elyria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and Pilling de <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, have said they'll pull out of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> before being forced to sign a contract with <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>. And the workers said Tuesday that they're concerned that if the plants are n't in operation, they'll close down. `` If the plants close down nobody is going to make sure we have jobs. We're not taking action against anybody. We just want to hold on to our jobs,'' said <PERSON> Nibco </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Alonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON>. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has not made a statement favoring one union leader or the other. Plant managers have made several trips to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> seeking an end to the conflict through the federal government. No decision had come Tuesday from either the courts or government officials. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, plant manager for the newly opened West Bend plant, said Tuesday that the workers' action proves their loyalty to <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>. `` It's a loud signal from the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> people to the government that they want their jobs and they want to work and work under the representation of <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>,'' said King, contacted in at the <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, just across the border from <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>. Asked when the American managers would return to the plants, <PERSON> King </PERSON> said, `` We have to wait and see what happens. We are continuing to try to solve this legally.''
