<HEAD>Cable Giant Posts Larger Loss in 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest cable television systems operator, said Tuesday its second-quarter loss widened to $ 63.6 million, citing higher interest expenses and increased losses by its affiliates. The company's loss for the three months ended June 30 was three times larger than its $ 21.9 million loss in the second quarter of 1988. Revenue for the second quarter rose 31.8 percent to $ 726.4 million from $ 551.0 million in the second quarter of 1988. The company said the increase in revenue was due to new cable television subscribers, increases in rates and acquisitions. <ORGANIZATION> TCI </ORGANIZATION> said its operating income rose to $ 142.6 million from $ 125.4 million a year earlier. Interest expenses, however, climbed to $ 205.9 million from $ 138.8 million a year earlier, and its share of losses by affiliates rose to $ 29.7 million from $ 400,000 in the second quarter of 1988. `` Consummation of the purchase of a 42.5 percent indirect interest in <ORGANIZATION> SCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and the business combination involving <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> have had a negative impact on <ORGANIZATION> TCI </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings due to the cost of servicing the indebtedness incurred to finance the transactions and the resulting increase in depreciation and amortization,'' the company said. For the first six months of the year, <ORGANIZATION> TCI </ORGANIZATION> recorded a net loss of $ 115 million compared with a loss of $ 29.2 million in the first half of 1988. Six-month revenue rose 31.4 percent to $ 1.38 billion from $ 1.05 billion a year earlier.
