<HEAD>Rebuilding Carrier Boosts Schedule; Cuts Fares</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with new grafs 1-10 to UPDATE with details of new fares,
schedule change; picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, Eastern union ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, trying to rebuild from a crippling strike and financial problems, on Tuesday expanded its schedule and cut its already discounted fares while adding the lure of refundable tickets. A union leader, meanwhile, said the new fare cuts for fall travel by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s healthier competitors would badly hurt <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to rebuild without its unions The discounts of up to $ 160 on a roundtrip fare were announced Sunday by <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and matched over the next two days by carriers including <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for marketing, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> had already planned new discounts before the other carriers and he said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s fall promotion offers tickets that `` are much easier to use and a much better value in most cases.'' Besides competitive rates, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s discounted fares, beginning Sept. 7, have fewer restrictions and unlike the other carriers, allow full refunds on unused tickets. `` We've been ... planning a major initiative for some time. Our fares are very, very different. Our fares are like going to an ATM -LRB- automatic teller machine -RRB- and theirs are like trying to get a mortgage,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said. Eastern will require only three - to-seven-day advance purchase and its low fares are available nearly every day and carry no restrictive penalties The fares will affect all domestic markets, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> said. The carrier increased Tuesday from 350 to 390 daily flights by adding 40 flights connecting <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and destinations mostly in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and said it would fly 600 daily flights starting Sept. 7. Eastern's rebuilding plan proposed to its creditors calls for 800 daily flights by year's end and an airline about two-thirds its pre-strike size. While <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> says it has hired enough new pilots and is keeping up with maintenance despite its strike, it has been leasing five planes and crews from sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said more planes and crews will be leased from <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as is Eastern, to meet the September expansion but that the practice is only temporary. Eastern union leaders, in their sixth month on strike, say the airline's claims to be coming back are misleading because their fares, as low as $ 39 one way, make it impossible to make money. `` The more they fly, the more they lose,'' Machinists District 100 President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> told a rally in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> on Saturday. <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s priority is winning back customers and the company is pleased at 75 percent load figures as its tries to come out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization. `` Indications are we're getting a warm welcome back,'' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. `` That's not to say that after a 5-month strike operating 10 percent of our service that there is n't a major challenge in rebuilding the airline. `` You have to first win back your customer base. We said in our business plan we would lose hundreds of millions of dollars between the comeback and the end of the year,'' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said in an interview Tuesday that consumers are going to go with the other airlines because `` they are very reliable, first-line carriers. They're not having phantom flights and people do n't have to worry about losing their money. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> tries to go even lower than the rest of the carriers, that's just going to compound their problems. It's going to doom the rebuilding plan, which was already doomed,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said. Before the strike that started March 4, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> normally had around $ 1 billion in revenue per quarter. Last quarter, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> posted $ 89.6 million in revenue. Management last week hurdled a major barrier to its rebuilding efforts when a split in pilots union ranks resulted in at least 250 more pilots returning to work, boosting to 650 the union crossovers. Eastern said with its own recruitment and training program it now has the 1,700 pilots needed for its rebuilding plan. Eastern is still hiring flight attendants and mechanics to replace strikers. The unions are backing a buyout bid by <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> and are lobbying in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for presidential and congressional intervention.
