<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar ended mixed in choppy trading Tuesday following a modest rise overseas. Gold prices firmed. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed up $ 3.60 at $ 370.70 a troy ounce. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid for gold at $ 368.50 an ounce, up $ 3.80 from Monday. Dealers said the dollar remained locked into a fairly narrow trading range in anticipation of new data that should shed more light on the economy and the short-term outlook for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates. The government is scheduled to release reports on industrial activity and housing starts for July on Wednesday, merchandise trade in June on Thursday, and the consumer price index on Friday. Some economists are predicting those reports will show continued economic growth, lessening the possibility of lower interest rates. The dollar has been boosted in recent days on speculation that interest rates wo n't fall any time soon. When rates remain firm, dollar-denominated securities, such as bonds, become more attractive to foreigners, and that increases the need for those investors to exchange their currencies for dollars. The dollar headed higher in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, although trading was subdued Tuesday due to the closing of markets in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> in observance of the Assumption Day religous holiday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose for the fourth consecutive trading day to 142.20 Japanese yen from 141.93 yen. It traded at 142.30 yen in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and at 142.15 yen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, up from 141.925 Monday. The British pound weakened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, falling to $ 1.5735 from $ 1.5840 late Monday. Sterling fetched $ 1.5768 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, down from $ 1.5770. Other dollar rates at Tuesday's close compared with late Monday, included: 1.9437 West German marks, down from 1.9485; 1.6748 Swiss francs, down from 1.6805; 1.18025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.17955; 6.5675 French francs, down from 6.5780; and 1,395.50 Italian lire, down from 1,399.00. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Monday: 1.9500 West German marks, up from 1.9395; 1.6790 Swiss francs, up from 1.6760; 6.5835 French francs, up from 6.5535; 2.1905 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1832; and 1.1822 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1775. Gold gained in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 365.75 an ounce, up from $ 364.00 bid Monday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold jumped to $ 366.25 an ounce from $ 363.50. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.42 to $ 365.72 an ounce. Silver prices rose. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $ 5.242 a troy ounce from $ 5.195 late Monday. Silver settled at $ 5.24 an ounce in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, up from $ 5.21.
