<HEAD>Chrysler Tentatively Plans 5 Percent Average Price Hike For 1990</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> tentatively plans to boost prices of its 1990 model cars by an average 5 percent, the automaker said Tuesday, and blames much of the rise on the cost of federally-mandated passenger restraints such as air bags. Price hikes outlined by the nation's third-largest automaker would boost the price of a <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> LeBaron coupe by 8.7 percent to $ 12,495 and of a subcompact <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horizon </ORGANIZATION> by 6.07 percent to $ 6,995, for example. The federal government is requiring that all cars made in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after Sept. 1 have driver-side air bags or automatic seat belts as standard equipment. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said they will install air bags on about 1 million cars each during the 1990 model year and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it will have the devices on about half as many. Earlier this week, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced a tentative 3.4 percent increase in its 1990 car prices, nearly 1 percent of it blamed on air bags. Ford Division General Manager <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> said earlier this month that his company will boost car prices about 4.8 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said Tuesday that air bags will add about $ 450 to the price of each U.S.-made <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> car, although that's less than the automaker actually is spending on buying and installing the devices. She declined to say exactly how much the company is spending on air bags. The rest of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s price increase stems from economic reasons, including higher material and labor costs, she said. Those figures are a bit lower than some analysts expected and may not include much padding for buyer incentives that can be factored into any car-buying deal. There has been speculation that the Big Three are eager to get out of the incentive war they have been in since early April. Incentives have cost the companies hundreds of dollars per car in recent months, cutting directly into profits. But a unilateral withdrawal from the rebate war may be tough, and consumers have grown accustomed to dealer offers of rebates and cut-rate financing. `` They're filing for pretty big price increases,'' said analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` But whether they will be real world or just on paper to be superseded with rebates is a good question.'' <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said he may have the answer: `` I think they will wait for about 15 minutes, see that -LRB- 1990 -RRB- sales are slow and come out with rebates.'' Firm retail prices will be announced during the next few weeks as the automakers introduce their 1990 cars. Although it is nearly certain that most 1990 cars will be more expensive than 1989s, some analysts say the sticker shock could be worse. `` If you look at an air bag cost and assume it's between $ 350 and $ 500,'' said analyst <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Laughlin </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, `` the price increases would not appear to be recovering the total costs of air bags and materials.''
