<HEAD>Car, Truck Sales Up 8.2 Percent In Early August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of cars and light trucks rose 8.2 percent in early August compared with last year, partly because of buying by consumers seeking to avoid price increases for 1990 cars, the companies reported Tuesday. Vehicles assembled by the eight major automakers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sold at an average daily rate of 33,660 during the Aug. 1-10 period this year, compared with a rate of 31,118 during the same time last year. Car sales rose 7.4 percent and truck sales were up 9.4 percent from the year-earlier period. In the last two seeks, the Big Three automakers have outlined tentative price hikes for cars in the model year that generally begins in October. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its tentative prices will be about 3.4 percent above 1989 levels, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said its prices will be about 4.8 percent higher and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s 1990 prices will be about 5 percent up from 1989. The companies said some of the increases are due to costs stemming from governmental requirements that they install passive restraint systems _ air bags or automatic seat belts _ in 1990 model cars. Some consumers may be pushing their 1990 car buying plans up a few months to miss the price boosts. `` I think in all probability there are people buying a little earlier than usual, but not many,'' said analyst <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. He said the picture would become a clearer later in the month as more sales reports are issued. Consumers also were lured by incentives, which automakers would like to drop during the coming model year. `` Car sales are a little stronger than I expected,'' said analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I would say it is the attractive rebates on the' 89s and the fear of costs of air bags. For Jan. 1 through Aug. 10, car and truck sales were 3.6 percent behind last year's pace, falling to an average daily rate of 38,063 this year from a rate of 39,500 last year. Car sales were off 4.8 percent and truck sales were down 1.5 percent during the period. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> car sales during the 10-day August period dropped 2.7 percent to a daily rate of 9,368 this year from 9,631 a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s sales for the year to date were 8.6 percent behind last year's pace <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s truck sales in early August were up 9.2 percent and for the year to date were 2.2 percent behind last year's pace. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s early August car sales rose to a rate of 6,826 a day, 17.6 percent up from a rate of 5,804 in the year-earlier period. For the year-to-date period, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were down 1.6 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> truck sales in early August were up 5.1 percent over last year. For the year through Aug. 10, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s truck sales were down 2.8 percent from last year's pace. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s early August car sales rose 5.6 percent to a daily rate of 2,835 this year from 2,685 daily a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales for the year to date were 14.1 percent behind last year's Truck sales were up 16.8 percent in early August for <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, while falling 0.2 percent from a year earlier for the Jan. 1-Aug. 10 period
