<HEAD>Oil Futures Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices finished mostly higher Tuesday in continued dull trading, buoyed mainly by technical market factors, traders said. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the September-delivery contract for <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, closed 10 cents higher at $ 18.68 per 42-gallon barrel. Contract months for later delivery posted smaller advances. Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded regular gasoline for September delivery slipped 0.3 cent to 52.06 cents a gallon. Most contracts for later delivery rose, however. Heating oil futures, which led the market higher last week, posted moderate gains. The September contract jumped 0.24 cent to finish at 50.28 cents a gallon. `` It's been very, very quiet in the market,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The market gained some momentum when the September crude contract hit the $ 18.50-per-barrel level, but other than that technical factor there was little to move prices, he said. The oil market has been in the summer doldrums for some time. Traders are looking forward to Labor Day for a pickup in activity and beyond that to the next scheduled meeting, on Sept. 23, of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
