<HEAD>Armand Hammer, Elated Over Bush Pardon, Usually Gets What He Wants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 14th graf, All the, with Oliver North
group calling for pardon; picks up 15th graf pvs, Born in .... Also moved
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON>, elated over his pardon by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for a Watergate-era crime, won a 13-year battle to clear his name with the same persistence and political savvy that made him a multibillionaire industrialist and intimate of world leaders. Hammer, 91, said on Monday he had been pardoned for making illegal contributions to President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s re-election campaign in 1972. Hammer had pleaded guilty to the charges in 1976, and was sentenced to one year's probation and fined $ 3,000. White House officials confirmed that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had pardoned Hammer and nine other unidentified people on Monday, but refused to give details. Repeated efforts to reach presidential counsel <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> were unsuccessful Tuesday. `` Having spent my lifetime fighting injustice, this vindication reinforces my abiding faith in the American system of justice,'' <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> said in a statement from his <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> home. `` I deeply appreciate President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s action in clearing my name.'' A spokesmen said Tuesday that Hammer, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, would have no further comment. Hammer spent several years seeking a pardon. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is known to have considered granting Hammer's wish before he left office last January, but nothing came of it. `` I'm pleading -LRB- guilty -RRB- because I'm guilty,'' Hammer had declared in federal court in 1976. But Hammer had blamed former Gov. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, a former vice president of an <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, through whom the $ 54,000 in illegal payments were made. Hammer argued that he funneled the money through <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> to maintain anonymity, but that <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> did not deliver the funds until after a new federal law went into effect in April 1972 which prohibited making campaign contributions in someone else's name. <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON> was sentenced to four months in prison and fined $ 1,000 for concealing the identity of Hammer as the actual donor. A federal judge later set aside <PERSON> Babcock </PERSON>'s prison term, partly because <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> was given probation instead of a prison term because of his age and poor health. Leaving his hospital bed as a heart patient for sentencing 13 years ago, <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> expressed regret over the first crime he had ever committed. He told the judge that `` I trust, in the time that may be left me, your honor will allow me to continue being a useful member of society.'' Since his brush with the law, Hammer has circled the globe in his specially outfitted <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 hobnobbing with presidents, kings and prime ministers, pushing for U.S.-Soviet summit talks, providing aid to earthquake victims, giving away chunks of his vast art collection and trying to raise $ 1 billion to find a cure for cancer. `` I've had two dreams, two ambitions in life, and I hope to accomplish both of them,'' he once said. They are peace between East and West and a cure for cancer. All the while, Hammer has guided <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION>'s growth from a struggling oil company worth $ 34,000 in 1956, when he made his first investment, into a colossus of oil, chemicals, coal and foods with a book value of more than $ 6 billion. His pardon was not universally applauded, however. A group called the Friends of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> decried the pardon for the man they said `` has been trying to encourage communist expansion through his open business dealings with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' The group called on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to `` muster the courage'' to pardon <PERSON> North </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide convicted of charges in the Iran-Contra affair. Born in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as the grandson of a Russian Jewish immigrant, Hammer became a millionaire while still studying at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, when he took over his physician father's faltering pharmaceutical business and turned it into a money-maker. At 23, he was fresh out of medical school but unwilling to wait six months to begin his internship at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. So in 1921, <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> made his first trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to help alleviate a typhus epidemic. Once there, <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> decided the Russian people needed food more than medical assistance. He quickly announced a deal that brought a shipload of surplus American wheat valued at $ 1 million in return for <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> furs, hides and caviar. That deal caught the attention of V.I. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, the first of many Soviet leaders Hammer has known. <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> encouraged the young American entrepreneur to take over an abandoned asbestos mine near western <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>, the first Soviet concession ever granted to a foreigner. Hammer developed the mine into a profitable enterprise, and soon obtained sales concessions for such leading American firms as <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rubber, <ORGANIZATION> Allis-Chalmers </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Underwood </PERSON> Typewriter. He also opened the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s first pencil factory, which posted $ 1 million in profits in the first year. Hammer left the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1930, taking his profits in the form of paintings, tapestries, silver and jewels, which formed the start of his multimillion-dollar art collection. He owns two art galleries in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. During the 1940s, Hammer netted a $ 7.5 million profit from a $ 100,000 investment by developing a way to turn surplus potato crops into commercial alcohol and marketing a blended whiskey under his own label. He accumulated seven distilleries and later sold his entire whiskey interests to the Schenley group. He also made fortunes in livestock feed and cattle, and held the nation's first million-dollar purebred <PERSON> Angus </PERSON> cattle sale. Even today, he is reaping fat profits from a $ 20 billion chemical fertilizer deal with the Soviets, and has joint coal mining and phosphoric acid ventures under way in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Commenting on his reputation as a worldwide wheeler-dealer, Hammer once said: `` I am first a catalyst. I bring people and situations together. That's the big thing _ bringing the deal together.''
</TEXT>
