<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-Congress-Computer Services listed on AM-Late News
Advisory. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary overcharged the government by $ 5.9 million on five computer projects between 1983 and 1987, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee said Tuesday. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, released a report from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the congressional auditing agency, detailing the overcharges by <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Like <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> said he was asking the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to seek recovery of the Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> had no immediate comment on the report. <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> also said he received a related but separate report from the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday suggesting that the Software Productivity Consortium, a group of 14 of the nation's leading defense firms established to develop tools and techniques to improve the productivity of military software, may have overcharged the government by $ 22.5 million for their participation in the consortium. In both cases, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said, the improper charges stemmed from misclassification of projects as `` manufacturing and production engineering,'' a category of expense for which contractors can be fully reimbursed by the government. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, however, concluded that both <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and the Software Productivity Consortium should have classified their activities as `` independent research and development'' expenditures, a classification of expenses for which the government contribution is limited. `` In this era of $ 300-billion military budgets and half-billion-dollar airplanes, $ 6 million may not seem like much, but that money could give 2,225 youngsters a chance in life by putting them through one year of Head Start,'' <PERSON> Conyers </PERSON> said in a statement.
