<HEAD>Mexico Opens Petroleum By-Products To Foreign Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TALLI NAUMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government has announced new rules allowing foreign investment in the nationalized petroleum industry, hoping to attract $ 8 billion over the next five years and modernize the industry. `` This is the first time we have defined clearly what foreign investment is allowed in petrochemical products,'' <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Elias </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petrochemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said at a news conference Tuesday. The commission has ruled that 15 oil-based products are now open to 40 percent private investment by foreign and domestic interests, <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> said. Those products were formerly reserved exclusively for the national oil company <ORGANIZATION> Petroleos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, also known as <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION>. The new rules also allow about 350 tertiary petrochemical products to be manufactured with 100 percent private investment. These include about 100 plastics products. Loosening <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION>'s grip on petroleum by-products follows a May announcement that the government was allowing greater foreign ownership in Mexican companies. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s administration has been striving to increase foreign investment and make the notoriously ineffectual oil industry more efficient and less corrupt. `` It's important for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to be integrated in world commerce and that we modernize technology,'' <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> said. The Mexican Constitution reserves primary petrochemical product manufacture to the government; only secondary and tertiary products come under the new ruling. The Energy, Mines and <ORGANIZATION> Parastate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> projects <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> investments of $ 1.5 billion through 1995. The government expects to attract an additional $ 8 billion from foreign and domestic private investors, <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> said. Foreign companies that have shown an interest in investing include <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Celanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, he added. The government hopes to increase petrochemical exports and decrease imports under the new scheme, he said. Investment of 40 percent will be allowed in producing vinyl acetate, acetone, acrylic acid, anhydrous acid, chlorobenzenes, ammonium phosphate, isoprene, isopropanal, ammonium nitrate, ammonium sulfate, polypropylenes and urea. These are all secondary products. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> will maintain exclusive control over 20 primary petrochemical products derived from the first refinement of crude oil. They include benzene, ethanol, methanol, propylene, N-paraffins and toluene.
