<HEAD>Dollar Down, Share Prices Climb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning Nikkei, dollar.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar opened lower and edged down relative to the Japanese yen Wednesday, while stock prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> continued their ascent for the second day. The dollar opened at 141.70 yen, down 0.50 yen from Tuesday's close of 142.20 yen It moved in the range of 141.40 to 141.75 yen and finished the morning session at 141.60 yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 139.07 points Tuesday, rose 193.32 points or 0.56 percent to finish the morning session at 35,004.01. Dealers said the dollar started lower following dollar selling in the <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> foreign exchange markets. <PERSON> Minoru </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozawa </PERSON>, a foreign exchange dealer with the <ORGANIZATION> Taiyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kobe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said dealers were positioning themselves before announcements later Wednesday of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> housing starts and investment utilization rates for July. `` There were no other reasons to sell,'' he said. On the stock exchange, <PERSON> Yoshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> said stocks were performing well in all sectors. He said that stock traders also were waiting for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> figures from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but were optimistic. Blue chips as well as laggard issues attracted buyer attention, <PERSON> Shimoyama </PERSON> said.
